626|"PREFACE"|FALSE
626|"The Author of the Book."|FALSE
626|"Richard de Bury (1281-1345), so called from being born near Bury St."|FALSE
626|"Edmunds, was the son of Sir Richard Aungerville. He studied at Oxford;"|FALSE
626|"and was subsequently chosen to be tutor to Prince Edward of Windsor,"|FALSE
626|"afterwards Edward III.  His loyalty to the cause of Queen Isabella and"|FALSE
626|"the Prince involved him in danger.  On the accession of his pupil he"|FALSE
626|"was made successively Cofferer, Treasurer of the Wardrobe, Archdeacon"|FALSE
626|"of Northampton, Prebendary of Lincoln, Sarum, and Lichfield, Keeper of"|FALSE
626|"the Privy Purse, Ambassador on two occasions to Pope John XXII, who"|FALSE
626|"appointed him a chaplain of the papal chapel, Dean of Wells, and"|FALSE
626|"ultimately, at the end of the year 1333, Bishop of Durham; the King and"|FALSE
626|"Queen, the King of Scots, and all the magnates north of the Trent,"|FALSE
626|"together with a multitude of nobles and many others, were present at"|FALSE
626|"his enthronization.  It is noteworthy that during his stay at Avignon,"|FALSE
626|"probably in 1330, he made the acquaintance of Petrarch, who has left us"|FALSE
626|"a brief account of their intercourse.  In 1332 Richard visited"|FALSE
626|"Cambridge, as one of the King's commissioners, to inquire into the"|FALSE
626|"state of the King's Scholars there, and perhaps then became a member of"|FALSE
626|"the Gild of St. Mary--one of the two gilds which founded Corpus Christi"|FALSE
626|"College."|FALSE
626|"In 1334 he became High Chancellor of England, and Treasurer in 1336,"|FALSE
626|"resigning the former office in 1335, so that he might help the King in"|FALSE
626|"dealing with affairs abroad and in Scotland, and took a most"|FALSE
626|"distinguished part in diplomatic negociations between England and"|FALSE
626|"France.  In 1339 he was again in his bishopric.  Thereafter his name"|FALSE
626|"occurs often among those appointed to treat of peace with Philip of"|FALSE
626|"France, and with Bruce of Scotland.  It appears that he was not in"|FALSE
626|"Parliament in 1344.  Wasted by long sickness--longa infirmitate"|FALSE
626|"decoctus--on the 14th of April, 1345, Richard de Bury died at Auckland,"|FALSE
626|"and was buried in Durham Cathedral."|FALSE
626|"Dominus Ricardus de Bury migravit ad Dominum."|FALSE
626|"The Bishop as Booklover."|FALSE
626|"According to the concluding note, the Philobiblon was completed on the"|FALSE
626|"bishop's fifty-eighth birthday, the 24th of January, 1345, so that even"|FALSE
626|"though weakened by illness, Richard must have been actively engaged in"|FALSE
626|"his literary efforts to the very end of his generous and noble life."|FALSE
626|"His enthusiastic devoted biographer Chambre[1] gives a vivid account of"|FALSE
626|"the bishop's bookloving propensities, supplementary to what can be"|FALSE
626|"gathered from the Philobiblon itself.  Iste summe delectabatur in"|FALSE
626|"multitudine librorum; he had more books, as was commonly reported, than"|FALSE
626|"all the other English bishops put together.  He had a separate library"|FALSE
626|"in each of his residences, and wherever he was residing, so many books"|FALSE
626|"lay about his bed-chamber, that it was hardly possible to stand or move"|FALSE
626|"without treading upon them.  All the time he could spare from business"|FALSE
626|"was devoted either to religious offices or to his books.  Every day"|FALSE
626|"while at table he would have a book read to him, unless some special"|FALSE
626|"guest were present, and afterwards would engage in discussion on the"|FALSE
626|"subject of the reading.  The haughty Anthony Bec delighted in the"|FALSE
626|"appendages of royalty--to be addressed by nobles kneeling, and to be"|FALSE
626|"waited on in his presence-chamber and at his table by Knights"|FALSE
626|"bare-headed and standing; but De Bury loved to surround himself with"|FALSE
626|"learned scholars.  Among these were such men as Thomas Bradwardine,"|FALSE
626|"afterwards Archbishop of Canterbury, and author of the De Causa Dei;"|FALSE
626|"Richard Fitzralph, afterwards Archbishop of Armagh, and famous for his"|FALSE
626|"hostility to the mendicant orders; Walter Burley, who dedicated to him"|FALSE
626|"a translation of the Politics of Aristotle made at his suggestion; John"|FALSE
626|"Mauduit, the astronomer; Robert Holkot, author of many books; Richard"|FALSE
626|"de Kilvington; Richard Benworth, afterwards Bishop of London; and"|FALSE
626|"Walter Seagrave, who became Dean of Chichester.\"[2]"|FALSE
626|"[1] Cp. Surtees Society's edition of Scriptores Tres; also Wharton's"|FALSE
626|"Anglia Sacra."|FALSE
626|"[2] An unsuccessful attempt has been made to transfer the authorship of"|FALSE
626|"the book to Robert Holkot.  Various theories have been advanced against"|FALSE
626|"Richard's claims.  It is noteworthy that his contemporary Adam Murimuth"|FALSE
626|"disparages him as \"mediocriter literatus, volens tamen magnus clericus"|FALSE
626|"reputari,\" but such disparagement must be taken with the utmost"|FALSE
626|"caution. The really difficult fact to be accounted for is the omission"|FALSE
626|"on the part of Chambre to mention the book."|FALSE
626|"The Bishop's Books."|FALSE
626|"In the Philobiblon, Richard de Bury frankly and clearly describes his"|FALSE
626|"means and method of collecting books.  Anyhow his object was clearly"|FALSE
626|"not selfish.  The treatise contains his rules for the library of the"|FALSE
626|"new College at Oxford--Durham College (where Trinity College now"|FALSE
626|"stands)--which he practically founded, though his successor, Bishop"|FALSE
626|"Hatfield, carried the scheme into effect.  It is traditionally reported"|FALSE
626|"that Richard's books were sent, in his lifetime or after his death, to"|FALSE
626|"the house of the Durham Benedictines at Oxford, and there remained"|FALSE
626|"until the dissolution of the College by Henry VIII., when they were"|FALSE
626|"dispersed, some going into Duke Humphrey's (the University) library,"|FALSE
626|"others to Balliol College, and the remainder passing into the hands of"|FALSE
626|"Dr. George Owen, who purchased the site of the dissolved College.[3]"|FALSE
626|"[3] Mr. J. W. Clark puts the matter as follows:--\"Durham College,"|FALSE
626|"maintained by the Benedictines of Durham, was supplied with books from"|FALSE
626|"the mother-house, lists of which have been preserved; and subsequently"|FALSE
626|"a library was built there to contain the collection bequeathed in 1345"|FALSE
626|"by Richard de Bury\" (The Care of Books, p.  142).  Mr. Thomas points"|FALSE
626|"out that De Bury's executors sold at least some portion of his books;"|FALSE
626|"and, moreover, his biographer says nothing of a library at Oxford."|FALSE
626|"Possibly the scheme was never carried out.  In the British Museum (Roy."|FALSE
626|"13 D. iv. 3) is a large folio MS. of the works of John of Salisbury,"|FALSE
626|"which was one of the books bought back from the Bishop's executors."|FALSE
626|"Unfortunately, the \"special catalogue\" of his books prepared by Richard"|FALSE
626|"has not come down to us; but \"from his own book and from the books"|FALSE
626|"cited in the works of his friends and housemates, who may reasonably be"|FALSE
626|"supposed to have drawn largely from the bishop's collection, it would"|FALSE
626|"be possible to restore a hypothetical but not improbable Bibliotheca"|FALSE
626|"Ricardi de Bury.  The difficulty would be with that contemporary"|FALSE
626|"literature, which they would think below the dignity of quotation, but"|FALSE
626|"which we know the Bishop collected.\""|FALSE
626|"Early Editions of the Philobiblon."|FALSE
626|"The book was first printed at Cologne in 1473, at Spires in 1483, and"|FALSE
626|"at Paris in 1500.  The first English edition appeared in 1598-9, edited"|FALSE
626|"by Thomas James, Bodley's first librarian.  Other editions appeared in"|FALSE
626|"Germany in 1610, 1614, 1674 and 1703; at Paris in 1856; at Albany in"|FALSE
626|"1861.  The texts were, with the exception of those issued in 1483 and"|FALSE
626|"1599, based on the 1473 edition; though the French edition and"|FALSE
626|"translation of 1856, prepared by M. Cocheris, claimed to be a critical"|FALSE
626|"version, it left the text untouched, and merely gave the various"|FALSE
626|"readings of the three Paris manuscripts at the foot of the pages; these"|FALSE
626|"readings are moreover badly chosen, and the faults of the version are"|FALSE
626|"further to be referred to the use of the ill-printed 1703 edition as"|FALSE
626|"copy."|FALSE
626|"In 1832 there appeared an anonymous English translation, now known to"|FALSE
626|"have been by J. B. Inglis; it followed the edition of 1473, with all"|FALSE
626|"its errors and inaccuracies."|FALSE
626|"Mr. E. C. Thomas' Text.--The first true text of the Philobiblon, the"|FALSE
626|"result of a careful examination of twenty-eight MSS., and of the"|FALSE
626|"various printed editions, appeared in the year 1888:"|FALSE
626|"\"The Philobiblon of Richard de Bury, Bishop of Durham, Treasurer and"|FALSE
626|"Chancellor of Edward III, edited and translated by Ernest C.  Thomas,"|FALSE
626|"Barrister-at-law, late Scholar of Trinity College, Oxford, and"|FALSE
626|"Librarian of the Oxford Union.  London: Kegan Paul, Trench, & Co.\""|FALSE
626|"For fifteen years the enthusiastic editor--an ideal Bibliophile--had"|FALSE
626|"toiled at his labour of love, and his work was on all sides received"|FALSE
626|"with the recognition due to his monumental achievement.  To the great"|FALSE
626|"loss of English learning, he did not long survive the conclusion of his"|FALSE
626|"labours.  The very limited edition of the work was soon exhausted, and"|FALSE
626|"it is by the most generous permission of his father, Mr. John Thomas,"|FALSE
626|"of Lower Broughton, Manchester, that the translation--the only"|FALSE
626|"trustworthy rendering of Richard de Bury's precious treatise--is now,"|FALSE
626|"for the first time, made accessible to the larger book-loving public,"|FALSE
626|"and fittingly inaugurates the present series of English classics.  The"|FALSE
626|"general Editor desires to express his best thanks to Mr. John Thomas,"|FALSE
626|"as also to Messrs. Kegan Paul, for their kindness in allowing him to"|FALSE
626|"avail himself of the materials included in the 1888 edition of the"|FALSE
626|"work.  He has attempted, in the brief Preface and Notes, to condense"|FALSE
626|"Mr. Thomas' labours in such a way as would have been acceptable to the"|FALSE
626|"lamented scholar, and though he has made bold to explain some few"|FALSE
626|"textual difficulties, and to add some few references, he would fain"|FALSE
626|"hope that these additions have been made with modest caution--with the"|FALSE
626|"reverence due to the unstinted toil of a Bibliophile after Richard de"|FALSE
626|"Bury's own pattern.  Yet once again Richard de Bury's Philobiblon,"|FALSE
626|"edited and translated into English by E. C. Thomas, is presented to new"|FALSE
626|"generations of book-lovers:--\"LIBRORUM DILECTORIBUS.\""|FALSE
