626|"PROLOGUE"|FALSE
626|"To all the faithful of Christ to whom the tenor of these presents may"|FALSE
626|"come, Richard de Bury, by the divine mercy Bishop of Durham, wisheth"|FALSE
626|"everlasting salvation in the Lord and to present continually a pious"|FALSE
626|"memorial of himself before God, alike in his lifetime and after his"|FALSE
626|"death."|FALSE
626|"What shall I render unto the Lord for all His benefits towards me? asks"|FALSE
626|"the most devout Psalmist, an invincible King and first among the"|FALSE
626|"prophets; in which most grateful question he approves himself a willing"|FALSE
626|"thank-offerer, a multifarious debtor, and one who wishes for a holier"|FALSE
626|"counsellor than himself: agreeing with Aristotle, the chief of"|FALSE
626|"philosophers, who shows (in the 3rd and 6th books of his Ethics) that"|FALSE
626|"all action depends upon counsel."|FALSE
626|"And indeed if so wonderful a prophet, having a fore-knowledge of divine"|FALSE
626|"secrets, wished so anxiously to consider how he might gratefully repay"|FALSE
626|"the blessings graciously bestowed, what can we fitly do, who are but"|FALSE
626|"rude thanksgivers and most greedy receivers, laden with infinite divine"|FALSE
626|"benefits?  Assuredly we ought with anxious deliberation and abundant"|FALSE
626|"consideration, having first invoked the Sevenfold Spirit, that it may"|FALSE
626|"burn in our musings as an illuminating fire, fervently to prepare a way"|FALSE
626|"without hinderance, that the bestower of all things may be cheerfully"|FALSE
626|"worshipped in return for the gifts that He has bestowed, that our"|FALSE
626|"neighbour may be relieved of his burden, and that the guilt contracted"|FALSE
626|"by sinners every day may be redeemed by the atonement of almsgiving."|FALSE
626|"Forewarned therefore through the admonition of the Psalmist's devotion"|FALSE
626|"by Him who alone prevents and perfects the goodwill of man, without"|FALSE
626|"Whom we have no power even so much as to think, and Whose gift we doubt"|FALSE
626|"not it is, if we have done anything good, we have diligently inquired"|FALSE
626|"and considered in our own heart as well as with others, what among the"|FALSE
626|"good offices of various works of piety would most please the Almighty,"|FALSE
626|"and would be more beneficial to the Church Militant.  And lo! there"|FALSE
626|"soon occurred to our contemplation a host of unhappy, nay, rather of"|FALSE
626|"elect scholars, in whom God the Creator and Nature His handmaid planted"|FALSE
626|"the roots of excellent morals and of famous sciences, but whom the"|FALSE
626|"poverty of their circumstances so oppressed that before the frown of"|FALSE
626|"adverse fortune the seeds of excellence, so fruitful in the cultivated"|FALSE
626|"field of youth, not being watered by the rain that they require, are"|FALSE
626|"forced to wither away. Thus it happens that \"bright virtue lurks buried"|FALSE
626|"in obscurity,\" to use the words of Boethius, and burning lights are not"|FALSE
626|"put under a bushel, but for want of oil are utterly extinguished.  Thus"|FALSE
626|"the field, so full of flower in Spring, has withered up before harvest"|FALSE
626|"time; thus wheat degenerates to tares, and vines into the wild vines,"|FALSE
626|"and thus olives run into the wild olive; the tender stems rot away"|FALSE
626|"altogether, and those who might have grown up into strong pillars of"|FALSE
626|"the Church, being endowed with the capacity of a subtle intellect,"|FALSE
626|"abandon the schools of learning.  With poverty only as their"|FALSE
626|"stepmother, they are repelled violently from the nectared cup of"|FALSE
626|"philosophy as soon as they have tasted of it and have become more"|FALSE
626|"fiercely thirsty by the very taste.  Though fit for the liberal arts"|FALSE
626|"and disposed to study the sacred writings alone, being deprived of the"|FALSE
626|"aid of their friends, by a kind of apostasy they return to the"|FALSE
626|"mechanical arts solely to gain a livelihood, to the loss of the Church"|FALSE
626|"and the degradation of the whole clergy.  Thus Mother Church conceiving"|FALSE
626|"sons is compelled to miscarry, nay, some misshapen monster is born"|FALSE
626|"untimely from her womb, and for lack of that little with which Nature"|FALSE
626|"is contented, she loses excellent pupils, who might afterwards become"|FALSE
626|"champions and athletes of the faith.  Alas, how suddenly the woof is"|FALSE
626|"cut, while the hand of the weaver is beginning his work! Alas, how the"|FALSE
626|"sun is eclipsed in the brightness of the dawn, and the planet in its"|FALSE
626|"course is hurled backwards, and, while it bears the nature and likeness"|FALSE
626|"of a star suddenly drops and becomes a meteor! What more piteous sight"|FALSE
626|"can the pious man behold? What can more sharply stir the bowels of his"|FALSE
626|"pity? What can more easily melt a heart hard as an anvil into hot"|FALSE
626|"tears? On the other hand, let us recall from past experience how much"|FALSE
626|"it has profited the whole Christian commonwealth, not indeed to"|FALSE
626|"enervate students with the delights of a Sardanapalus or the riches of"|FALSE
626|"a Croesus, but rather to support them in their poverty with the frugal"|FALSE
626|"means that become the scholar.  How many have we seen with our eyes,"|FALSE
626|"how many have we read of in books, who, distinguished by no pride of"|FALSE
626|"birth, and rejoicing in no rich inheritance, but supported only by the"|FALSE
626|"piety of the good, have made their way to apostolic chairs, have most"|FALSE
626|"worthily presided over faithful subjects, have bent the necks of the"|FALSE
626|"proud and lofty to the ecclesiastical yoke and have extended further"|FALSE
626|"the liberties of the Church!"|FALSE
626|"Accordingly, having taken a survey of human necessities in every"|FALSE
626|"direction, with a view to bestow our charity upon them, our"|FALSE
626|"compassionate inclinations have chosen to bear pious aid to this"|FALSE
626|"calamitous class of men, in whom there is nevertheless such hope of"|FALSE
626|"advantage to the Church, and to provide for them, not only in respect"|FALSE
626|"of things necessary to their support, but much more in respect of the"|FALSE
626|"books so useful to their studies.  To this end, most acceptable in the"|FALSE
626|"sight of God, our attention has long been unweariedly devoted.  This"|FALSE
626|"ecstatic love has carried us away so powerfully, that we have resigned"|FALSE
626|"all thoughts of other earthly things, and have given ourselves up to a"|FALSE
626|"passion for acquiring books.  That our intent and purpose, therefore,"|FALSE
626|"may be known to posterity as well as to our contemporaries, and that we"|FALSE
626|"may for ever stop the perverse tongues of gossipers as far as we are"|FALSE
626|"concerned, we have published a little treatise written in the lightest"|FALSE
626|"style of the moderns; for it is ridiculous to find a slight matter"|FALSE
626|"treated of in a pompous style.  And this treatise (divided into twenty"|FALSE
626|"chapters) will clear the love we have had for books from the charge of"|FALSE
626|"excess, will expound the purpose of our intense devotion, and will"|FALSE
626|"narrate more clearly than light all the circumstances of our"|FALSE
626|"undertaking.  And because it principally treats of the love of books,"|FALSE
626|"we have chosen, after the fashion of the ancient Romans, fondly to name"|FALSE
626|"it by a Greek word, Philobiblon."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER I"|FALSE
626|"THAT THE TREASURE OF WISDOM IS CHIEFLY CONTAINED IN BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"The desirable treasure of wisdom and science, which all men desire by"|FALSE
626|"an instinct of nature, infinitely surpasses all the riches of the"|FALSE
626|"world; in respect of which precious stones are worthless; in comparison"|FALSE
626|"with which silver is as clay and pure gold is as a little sand; at"|FALSE
626|"whose splendour the sun and moon are dark to look upon; compared with"|FALSE
626|"whose marvellous sweetness honey and manna are bitter to the taste.  O"|FALSE
626|"value of wisdom that fadeth not away with time, virtue ever"|FALSE
626|"flourishing, that cleanseth its possessor from all venom!  O heavenly"|FALSE
626|"gift of the divine bounty, descending from the Father of lights, that"|FALSE
626|"thou mayest exalt the rational soul to the very heavens!  Thou art the"|FALSE
626|"celestial nourishment of the intellect, which those who eat shall still"|FALSE
626|"hunger and those who drink shall still thirst, and the gladdening"|FALSE
626|"harmony of the languishing soul which he that hears shall never be"|FALSE
626|"confounded.  Thou art the moderator and rule of morals, which he who"|FALSE
626|"follows shall not sin.  By thee kings reign and princes decree justice."|FALSE
626|"By thee, rid of their native rudeness, their minds and tongues being"|FALSE
626|"polished, the thorns of vice being torn up by the roots, those men"|FALSE
626|"attain high places of honour, and become fathers of their country, and"|FALSE
626|"companions of princes, who without thee would have melted their spears"|FALSE
626|"into pruning-hooks and ploughshares, or would perhaps be feeding swine"|FALSE
626|"with the prodigal."|FALSE
626|"Where dost thou chiefly lie hidden, O most elect treasure! and where"|FALSE
626|"shall thirsting souls discover thee?"|FALSE
626|"Certes, thou hast placed thy tabernacle in books, where the Most High,"|FALSE
626|"the Light of lights, the Book of Life, has established thee.  There"|FALSE
626|"everyone who asks receiveth thee, and everyone who seeks finds thee,"|FALSE
626|"and to everyone that knocketh boldly it is speedily opened.  Therein"|FALSE
626|"the cherubim spread out their wings, that the intellect of the students"|FALSE
626|"may ascend and look from pole to pole, from the east and west, from the"|FALSE
626|"north and from the south.  Therein the mighty and incomprehensible God"|FALSE
626|"Himself is apprehensibly contained and worshipped; therein is revealed"|FALSE
626|"the nature of things celestial, terrestrial, and infernal; therein are"|FALSE
626|"discerned the laws by which every state is administered, the offices of"|FALSE
626|"the celestial hierarchy are distinguished, and the tyrannies of demons"|FALSE
626|"described, such as neither the ideas of Plato transcend, nor the chair"|FALSE
626|"of Crato contained."|FALSE
626|"In books I find the dead as if they were alive; in books I foresee"|FALSE
626|"things to come; in books warlike affairs are set forth; from books come"|FALSE
626|"forth the laws of peace.  All things are corrupted and decay in time;"|FALSE
626|"Saturn ceases not to devour the children that he generates; all the"|FALSE
626|"glory of the world would be buried in oblivion, unless God had provided"|FALSE
626|"mortals with the remedy of books."|FALSE
626|"Alexander, the conqueror of the earth, Julius, the invader of Rome and"|FALSE
626|"of the world, who, the first in war and arts, assumed universal empire"|FALSE
626|"under his single rule, faithful Fabricius and stern Cato, would now"|FALSE
626|"have been unknown to fame, if the aid of books had been wanting."|FALSE
626|"Towers have been razed to the ground; cities have been overthrown;"|FALSE
626|"triumphal arches have perished from decay; nor can either pope or king"|FALSE
626|"find any means of more easily conferring the privilege of perpetuity"|FALSE
626|"than by books.  The book that he has made renders its author this"|FALSE
626|"service in return, that so long as the book survives its author remains"|FALSE
626|"immortal and cannot die, as Ptolemy declares in the Prologue to his"|FALSE
626|"Almagest: He is not dead, he says, who has given life to science."|FALSE
626|"Who therefore will limit by anything of another kind the price of the"|FALSE
626|"infinite treasure of books, from which the scribe who is instructed"|FALSE
626|"bringeth forth things new and old?  Truth that triumphs over all"|FALSE
626|"things, which overcomes the king, wine, and women, which it is reckoned"|FALSE
626|"holy to honour before friendship, which is the way without turning and"|FALSE
626|"the life without end, which holy Boethius considers to be threefold in"|FALSE
626|"thought, speech, and writing, seems to remain more usefully and to"|FALSE
626|"fructify to greater profit in books.  For the meaning of the voice"|FALSE
626|"perishes with the sound; truth latent in the mind is wisdom that is hid"|FALSE
626|"and treasure that is not seen; but truth which shines forth in books"|FALSE
626|"desires to manifest itself to every impressionable sense.  It commends"|FALSE
626|"itself to the sight when it is read, to the hearing when it is heard,"|FALSE
626|"and moreover in a manner to the touch, when it suffers itself to be"|FALSE
626|"transcribed, bound, corrected, and preserved.   The undisclosed truth"|FALSE
626|"of the mind, although it is the possession of the noble soul, yet"|FALSE
626|"because it lacks a companion, is not certainly known to be delightful,"|FALSE
626|"while neither sight nor hearing takes account of it.  Further the truth"|FALSE
626|"of the voice is patent only to the ear and eludes the sight, which"|FALSE
626|"reveals to us more of the qualities of things, and linked with the"|FALSE
626|"subtlest of motions begins and perishes as it were in a breath.  But"|FALSE
626|"the written truth of books, not transient but permanent, plainly offers"|FALSE
626|"itself to be observed, and by means of the pervious spherules of the"|FALSE
626|"eyes, passing through the vestibule of perception and the courts of"|FALSE
626|"imagination, enters the chamber of intellect, taking its place in the"|FALSE
626|"couch of memory, where it engenders the eternal truth of the mind."|FALSE
626|"Finally we must consider what pleasantness of teaching there is in"|FALSE
626|"books, how easy, how secret! How safely we lay bare the poverty of"|FALSE
626|"human ignorance to books without feeling any shame!  They are masters"|FALSE
626|"who instruct us without rod or ferule, without angry words, without"|FALSE
626|"clothes or money.  If you come to them they are not asleep; if you ask"|FALSE
626|"and inquire of them they do not withdraw themselves; they do not chide"|FALSE
