626|"CHAPTER II"|FALSE
626|"THE DEGREE OF AFFECTION THAT IS PROPERLY DUE TO BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"Since the degree of affection a thing deserves depends upon the degree"|FALSE
626|"of its value, and the previous chapter shows that the value of books is"|FALSE
626|"unspeakable, it is quite clear to the reader what is the probable"|FALSE
626|"conclusion from this.  I say probable, for in moral science we do not"|FALSE
626|"insist upon demonstration, remembering that the educated man seeks such"|FALSE
626|"degree of certainty as he perceives the subject-matter will bear, as"|FALSE
626|"Aristotle testifies in the first book of his Ethics.  For Tully does"|FALSE
626|"not appeal to Euclid, nor does Euclid rely upon Tully.  This at all"|FALSE
626|"events we endeavour to prove, whether by logic or rhetoric, that all"|FALSE
626|"riches and all delights whatsoever yield place to books in the"|FALSE
626|"spiritual mind, wherein the Spirit which is charity ordereth charity."|FALSE
626|"Now in the first place, because wisdom is contained in books more than"|FALSE
626|"all mortals understand, and wisdom thinks lightly of riches, as the"|FALSE
626|"foregoing chapter declares.  Furthermore, Aristotle, in his Problems,"|FALSE
626|"determines the question, why the ancients proposed prizes to the"|FALSE
626|"stronger in gymnastic and corporeal contests, but never awarded any"|FALSE
626|"prize for wisdom.  This question he solves as follows:  In gymnastic"|FALSE
626|"exercises the prize is better and more desirable than that for which it"|FALSE
626|"is bestowed; but it is certain that nothing is better than wisdom:"|FALSE
626|"wherefore no prize could be assigned for wisdom.  And therefore neither"|FALSE
626|"riches nor delights are more excellent than wisdom.  Again, only the"|FALSE
626|"fool will deny that friendship is to be preferred to riches, since the"|FALSE
626|"wisest of men testifies this; but the chief of philosophers honours"|FALSE
626|"truth before friendship, and the truthful Zorobabel prefers it to all"|FALSE
626|"things.  Riches, then, are less than truth.  Now truth is chiefly"|FALSE
626|"maintained and contained in holy books--nay, they are written truth"|FALSE
626|"itself, since by books we do not now mean the materials of which they"|FALSE
626|"are made.  Wherefore riches are less than books, especially as the most"|FALSE
626|"precious of all riches are friends, as Boethius testifies in the second"|FALSE
626|"book of his Consolation; to whom the truth of books according to"|FALSE
626|"Aristotle is to be preferred.  Moreover, since we know that riches"|FALSE
626|"first and chiefly appertain to the support of the body only, while the"|FALSE
626|"virtue of books is the perfection of reason, which is properly speaking"|FALSE
626|"the happiness of man, it appears that books to the man who uses his"|FALSE
626|"reason are dearer than riches.  Furthermore, that by which the faith is"|FALSE
626|"more easily defended, more widely spread, more clearly preached, ought"|FALSE
626|"to be more desirable to the faithful.  But this is the truth written in"|FALSE
626|"books, which our Saviour plainly showed, when he was about to contend"|FALSE
626|"stoutly against the Tempter, girding himself with the shield of truth"|FALSE
626|"and indeed of written truth, declaring \"it is written\" of what he was"|FALSE
626|"about to utter with his voice."|FALSE
626|"And, again, no one doubts that happiness is to be preferred to riches."|FALSE
626|"But happiness consists in the operation of the noblest and diviner of"|FALSE
626|"the faculties that we possess--when the whole mind is occupied in"|FALSE
626|"contemplating the truth of wisdom, which is the most delectable of all"|FALSE
626|"our virtuous activities, as the prince of philosophers declares in the"|FALSE
626|"tenth book of the Ethics, on which account it is that philosophy is"|FALSE
626|"held to have wondrous pleasures in respect of purity and solidity, as"|FALSE
626|"he goes on to say.  But the contemplation of truth is never more"|FALSE
626|"perfect than in books, where the act of imagination perpetuated by"|FALSE
626|"books does not suffer the operation of the intellect upon the truths"|FALSE
626|"that it has seen to suffer interruption.  Wherefore books appear to be"|FALSE
626|"the most immediate instruments of speculative delight, and therefore"|FALSE
626|"Aristotle, the sun of philosophic truth, in considering the principles"|FALSE
626|"of choice, teaches that in itself to philosophize is more desirable"|FALSE
626|"than to be rich, although in certain cases, as where for instance one"|FALSE
626|"is in need of necessaries, it may be more desirable to be rich than to"|FALSE
626|"philosophize."|FALSE
626|"Moreover, since books are the aptest teachers, as the previous chapter"|FALSE
626|"assumes, it is fitting to bestow on them the honour and the affection"|FALSE
626|"that we owe to our teachers.  In fine, since all men naturally desire"|FALSE
626|"to know, and since by means of books we can attain the knowledge of the"|FALSE
626|"ancients, which is to be desired beyond all riches, what man living"|FALSE
626|"according to nature would not feel the desire of books?  And although"|FALSE
626|"we know that swine trample pearls under foot, the wise man will not"|FALSE
626|"therefore be deterred from gathering the pearls that lie before him.  A"|FALSE
626|"library of wisdom, then, is more precious than all wealth, and all"|FALSE
626|"things that are desirable cannot be compared to it.  Whoever therefore"|FALSE
626|"claims to be zealous of truth, of happiness, of wisdom or knowledge,"|FALSE
626|"aye, even of the faith, must needs become a lover of books."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER III"|FALSE
626|"WHAT WE ARE TO THINK OF THE PRICE IN THE BUYING OF BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"From what has been said we draw this corollary welcome to us, but (as"|FALSE
626|"we believe) acceptable to few: namely, that no dearness of price ought"|FALSE
626|"to hinder a man from the buying of books, if he has the money that is"|FALSE
626|"demanded for them, unless it be to withstand the malice of the seller"|FALSE
626|"or to await a more favourable opportunity of buying.  For if it is"|FALSE
626|"wisdom only that makes the price of books, which is an infinite"|FALSE
626|"treasure to mankind, and if the value of books is unspeakable, as the"|FALSE
626|"premises show, how shall the bargain be shown to be dear where an"|FALSE
626|"infinite good is being bought? Wherefore, that books are to be gladly"|FALSE
626|"bought and unwillingly sold, Solomon, the sun of men, exhorts us in the"|FALSE
626|"Proverbs: Buy the truth, he says, and sell not wisdom.  But what we are"|FALSE
626|"trying to show by rhetoric or logic, let us prove by examples from"|FALSE
626|"history.  The arch-philosopher Aristotle, whom Averroes regards as the"|FALSE
626|"law of Nature, bought a few books of Speusippus straightway after his"|FALSE
626|"death for 72,000 sesterces.  Plato, before him in time, but after him"|FALSE
626|"in learning, bought the book of Philolaus the Pythagorean, from which"|FALSE
626|"he is said to have taken the Timaeus, for 10,000 denaries, as Aulus"|FALSE
626|"Gellius relates in the Noctes Atticae. Now Aulus Gellius relates this"|FALSE
626|"that the foolish may consider how wise men despise money in comparison"|FALSE
626|"with books.  And on the other hand, that we may know that folly and"|FALSE
626|"pride go together, let us here relate the folly of Tarquin the Proud in"|FALSE
626|"despising books, as also related by Aulus Gellius.  An old woman,"|FALSE
626|"utterly unknown, is said to have come to Tarquin the Proud, the seventh"|FALSE
626|"king of Rome, offering to sell nine books, in which (as she declared)"|FALSE
626|"sacred oracles were contained, but she asked an immense sum for them,"|FALSE
626|"insomuch that the king said she was mad.  In anger she flung three"|FALSE
626|"books into the fire, and still asked the same sum for the rest.  When"|FALSE
626|"the king refused it, again she flung three others into the fire and"|FALSE
626|"still asked the same price for the three that were left.  At last,"|FALSE
626|"astonished beyond measure, Tarquin was glad to pay for three books the"|FALSE
626|"same price for which he might have bought nine.  The old woman"|FALSE
626|"straightway disappeared, and was never seen before or after.  These"|FALSE
626|"were the Sibylline books, which the Romans consulted as a divine oracle"|FALSE
626|"by some one of the Quindecemvirs, and this is believed to have been the"|FALSE
626|"origin of the Quindecemvirate.  What did this Sibyl teach the proud"|FALSE
626|"king by this bold deed, except that the vessels of wisdom, holy books,"|FALSE
626|"exceed all human estimation; and, as Gregory says of the kingdom of"|FALSE
626|"Heaven:  They are worth all that thou hast?"|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER IV"|FALSE
626|"THE COMPLAINT OF BOOKS AGAINST THE CLERGY ALREADY PROMOTED"|FALSE
626|"A generation of vipers destroying their own parent and base offspring"|FALSE
626|"of the ungrateful cuckoo, who when he has grown strong slays his nurse,"|FALSE
626|"the giver of his strength, are degenerate clerks with regard to books."|FALSE
626|"Bring it again to mind and consider faithfully what ye receive through"|FALSE
626|"books, and ye will find that books are as it were the creators of your"|FALSE
626|"distinction, without which other favourers would have been wanting."|FALSE
626|"In sooth, while still untrained and helpless ye crept up to us, ye"|FALSE
626|"spake as children, ye thought as children, ye cried as children and"|FALSE
626|"begged to be made partakers of our milk.  But we being straightway"|FALSE
626|"moved by your tears gave you the breast of grammar to suck, which ye"|FALSE
626|"plied continually with teeth and tongue, until ye lost your native"|FALSE
626|"barbarousness and learned to speak with our tongues the mighty things"|FALSE
626|"of God.  And next we clad you with the goodly garments of philosophy,"|FALSE
626|"rhetoric and dialectic, of which we had and have a store, while ye were"|FALSE
626|"naked as a tablet to be painted on.  For all the household of"|FALSE
626|"philosophy are clothed with garments, that the nakedness and rawness of"|FALSE
626|"the intellect may be covered. After this, providing you with the"|FALSE
626|"fourfold wings of the quadrivials that ye might be winged like the"|FALSE
626|"seraphs and so mount above the cherubim, we sent you to a friend at"|FALSE
626|"whose door, if only ye importunately knocked, ye might borrow the three"|FALSE
626|"loaves of the Knowledge of the Trinity, in which consists the final"|FALSE
626|"felicity of every sojourner below.  Nay, if ye deny that ye had these"|FALSE
626|"privileges, we boldly declare that ye either lost them by your"|FALSE
626|"carelessness, or that through your sloth ye spurned them when offered"|FALSE
626|"to you. If these things seem but a light matter to you, we will add yet"|FALSE
626|"greater things.  Ye are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy"|FALSE
626|"race, ye are a peculiar people chosen into the lot of God, ye are"|FALSE
