626|"as a fattened holocaust to Vulcan, or at least may be hung up as a"|FALSE
626|"victim to Juno: while our nursling at a single reading of the book of"|FALSE
626|"life is handed over to the custody of the Bishop, and rigour is changed"|FALSE
626|"to favour, and the forum being transferred from the laity, death is"|FALSE
626|"routed by the clerk who is the nursling of books."|FALSE
626|"But now let us speak of the clerks who are vessels of virtue.  Which of"|FALSE
626|"you about to preach ascends the pulpit or the rostrum without in some"|FALSE
626|"way consulting us?  Which of you enters the schools to teach or to"|FALSE
626|"dispute without relying upon our support?  First of all, it behoves you"|FALSE
626|"to eat the book with Ezechiel, that the belly of your memory may be"|FALSE
626|"sweetened within, and thus as with the panther refreshed, to whose"|FALSE
626|"breath all beasts and cattle long to approach, the sweet savour of the"|FALSE
626|"spices it has eaten may shed a perfume without.  Thus our nature"|FALSE
626|"secretly working in our own, listeners hasten up gladly, as the"|FALSE
626|"load-stone draws the iron nothing loth.  What an infinite host of books"|FALSE
626|"lie at Paris or Athens, and at the same time resound in Britain and in"|FALSE
626|"Rome! In truth, while resting they yet move, and while retaining their"|FALSE
626|"own places they are carried about every way to the minds of listeners."|FALSE
626|"Finally, by the knowledge of literature, we establish Priests, Bishops,"|FALSE
626|"Cardinals, and the Pope, that all things in the ecclesiastical"|FALSE
626|"hierarchy may be fitly disposed.  For it is from books that everything"|FALSE
626|"of good that befalls the clerical condition takes its origin.  But let"|FALSE
626|"this suffice: for it pains us to recall what we have bestowed upon the"|FALSE
626|"degenerate clergy, because whatever gifts are distributed to the"|FALSE
626|"ungrateful seem to be lost rather than bestowed."|FALSE
626|"Let us next dwell a little on the recital of the wrongs with which they"|FALSE
626|"requite us, the contempts and cruelties of which we cannot recite an"|FALSE
626|"example in each kind, nay, scarcely the main classes of the several"|FALSE
626|"wrongs.  In the first place, we are expelled by force and arms from the"|FALSE
626|"homes of the clergy, which are ours by hereditary right, who were used"|FALSE
626|"to have cells of quietness in the inner chamber, but, alas! in these"|FALSE
626|"unhappy times we are altogether exiled, suffering poverty without the"|FALSE
626|"gates.  For our places are seized now by dogs, now by hawks, now by"|FALSE
626|"that biped beast whose cohabitation with the clergy was forbidden of"|FALSE
626|"old, from which we have always taught our nurslings to flee more than"|FALSE
626|"from the asp and the cockatrice; wherefore she, always jealous of the"|FALSE
626|"love of us, and never to be appeased, at length seeing us in some"|FALSE
626|"corner protected only by the web of some dead spider, with a frown"|FALSE
626|"abuses and reviles us with bitter words, declaring us alone of all the"|FALSE
626|"furniture in the house to be unnecessary, and complaining that we are"|FALSE
626|"useless for any household purpose, and advises that we should speedily"|FALSE
626|"be converted into rich caps, sendal and silk and twice-dyed purple,"|FALSE
626|"robes and furs, wool and linen: and, indeed, not without reason, if she"|FALSE
626|"could see our inmost hearts, if she had listened to our secret"|FALSE
626|"counsels, if she had read the book of Theophrastus or Valerius, or only"|FALSE
626|"heard the twenty-fifth chapter of Ecclesiasticus with understanding"|FALSE
626|"ears."|FALSE
626|"And hence it is that we have to mourn for the homes of which we have"|FALSE
626|"been unjustly robbed; and as to our coverings, not that they have not"|FALSE
626|"been given to us, but that the coverings anciently given to us have"|FALSE
