626|"into the power of laymen, which is more bitter to us than any death,"|FALSE
626|"since they have sold our people for nought, and our enemies themselves"|FALSE
626|"are our judges."|FALSE
626|"It is clear from what we have said what infinite invectives we could"|FALSE
626|"hurl against the clergy, if we did not think of our own reputation."|FALSE
626|"For the soldier whose campaigns are over venerates his shield and arms,"|FALSE
