626|"flight of the finest volumes."|FALSE
626|"And this is what we undertook to narrate in the present chapter."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER IX"|FALSE
626|"HOW, ALTHOUGH WE PREFERRED THE WORKS OF THE ANCIENTS, WE HAVE NOT"|FALSE
626|"CONDEMNED THE STUDIES OF THE MODERNS"|FALSE
626|"Although the novelties of the moderns were never disagreeable to our"|FALSE
626|"desires, who have always cherished with grateful affection those who"|FALSE
626|"devote themselves to study and who add anything either ingenious or"|FALSE
626|"useful to the opinions of our forefathers, yet we have always desired"|FALSE
626|"with more undoubting avidity to investigate the well-tested labours of"|FALSE
626|"the ancients.  For whether they had by nature a greater vigour of"|FALSE
626|"mental sagacity, or whether they perhaps indulged in closer application"|FALSE
626|"to study, or whether they were assisted in their progress by both these"|FALSE
626|"things, one thing we are perfectly clear about, that their successors"|FALSE
626|"are barely capable of discussing the discoveries of their forerunners,"|FALSE
626|"and of acquiring those things as pupils which the ancients dug out by"|FALSE
626|"difficult efforts of discovery.  For as we read that the men of old"|FALSE
626|"were of a more excellent degree of bodily development than modern times"|FALSE
626|"are found to produce, it is by no means absurd to suppose that most of"|FALSE
626|"the ancients were distinguished by brighter faculties, seeing that in"|FALSE
626|"the labours they accomplished of both kinds they are inimitable by"|FALSE
626|"posterity.   And so Phocas writes in the prologue to his Grammar:"|FALSE
626|"     Since all things have been said by men of sense"|FALSE
626|"     The only novelty is--to condense."|FALSE
626|"But in truth, if we speak of fervour of learning and diligence in"|FALSE
626|"study, they gave up all their lives to philosophy; while nowadays our"|FALSE
626|"contemporaries carelessly spend a few years of hot youth, alternating"|FALSE
626|"with the excesses of vice, and when the passions have been calmed, and"|FALSE
626|"they have attained the capacity of discerning truth so difficult to"|FALSE
626|"discover, they soon become involved in worldly affairs and retire,"|FALSE
626|"bidding farewell to the schools of philosophy.  They offer the fuming"|FALSE
626|"must of their youthful intellect to the  difficulties of philosophy,"|FALSE
626|"and bestow the clearer wine upon the money-making business of life."|FALSE
626|"Further, as Ovid in the first book of the De Vetula justly complains:"|FALSE
626|"  The hearts of all men after gold aspire;"|FALSE
626|"  Few study to be wise, more to acquire:"|FALSE
626|"  Thus, Science! all thy virgin charms are sold,"|FALSE
626|"  Whose chaste embraces should disdain their gold,"|FALSE
626|"  Who seek not thee thyself, but pelf through thee,"|FALSE
626|"  Longing for riches, not philosophy."|FALSE
626|"And further on:"|FALSE
626|"  Thus Philosophy is seen"|FALSE
626|"  Exiled, and Philopecuny is queen,"|FALSE
626|"which is known to be the most violent poison of learning."|FALSE
626|"How the ancients indeed regarded life as the only limit of study, is"|FALSE
626|"shown by Valerius, in his book addressed to Tiberius, by many examples."|FALSE
626|"Carneades, he says, was a laborious and lifelong soldier of wisdom:"|FALSE
626|"after he had lived ninety years, the same day put an end to his life"|FALSE
626|"and his philosophizing.  Isocrates in his ninety-fourth year wrote a"|FALSE
626|"most noble work.  Sophocles did the same when nearly a hundred years"|FALSE
626|"old.  Simonides wrote poems in his eightieth year.  Aulus Gellius did"|FALSE
626|"not desire to live longer than he should be able to write, as he says"|FALSE
626|"himself in the prologue to the Noctes Atticae."|FALSE
626|"The fervour of study which possessed Euclid the Socratic, Taurus the"|FALSE
626|"philosopher used to relate to incite young men to study, as Gellius"|FALSE
626|"tells in the book we have mentioned.  For the Athenians, hating the"|FALSE
626|"people of Megara, decreed that if any of the Megarensians entered"|FALSE
626|"Athens, he should be put to death.  Then Euclid, who was a Megarensian,"|FALSE
626|"and had attended the lectures of Socrates before this decree,"|FALSE
626|"disguising himself in a woman's dress, used to go from Megara to Athens"|FALSE
626|"by night to hear Socrates, a distance of twenty miles and back."|FALSE
626|"Imprudent and excessive was the fervour of Archimedes, a lover of"|FALSE
626|"geometry, who would not declare his name, nor lift his head from the"|FALSE
626|"diagram he had drawn, by which he might have prolonged his life, but"|FALSE
626|"thinking more of study than of life dyed with his life-blood the figure"|FALSE
626|"he was studying."|FALSE
626|"There are very many such examples of our proposition, but the brevity"|FALSE
626|"we aim at does not allow us to recall them.  But, painful to relate,"|FALSE
626|"the clerks who are famous in these days pursue a very different course."|FALSE
626|"Afflicted with ambition in their tender years, and slightly fastening"|FALSE
626|"to their untried arms the Icarian wings of presumption, they"|FALSE
626|"prematurely snatch the master's cap; and mere boys become unworthy"|FALSE
626|"professors of the several faculties, through which they do not make"|FALSE
626|"their way step by step, but like goats ascend by leaps and bounds; and,"|FALSE
626|"having slightly tasted of the mighty stream, they think that they have"|FALSE
626|"drunk it dry, though their throats are hardly moistened.  And because"|FALSE
626|"they are not grounded in the first rudiments at the fitting time, they"|FALSE
626|"build a tottering edifice on an unstable foundation, and now that they"|FALSE
626|"have grown up, they are ashamed to learn what they ought to have"|FALSE
626|"learned while young, and thus they are compelled to suffer for ever for"|FALSE
626|"too hastily jumping at dignities they have not deserved.  For these and"|FALSE
626|"the like reasons the tyros in the schools do not attain to the solid"|FALSE
626|"learning of the ancients in a few short hours of study, although they"|FALSE
626|"may enjoy distinctions, may be accorded titles, be authorized by"|FALSE
626|"official robes, and solemnly installed in the chairs of the elders."|FALSE
626|"Just snatched from the cradle and hastily weaned, they mouth the rules"|FALSE
626|"of Priscian and Donatus; while still beardless boys they gabble with"|FALSE
626|"childish stammering the Categorics and Peri Hermeneias, in the writing"|FALSE
626|"of which the great Aristotle is said to have dipped his pen in his"|FALSE
626|"heart's blood.  Passing through these faculties with baneful haste and"|FALSE
626|"a harmful diploma, they lay violent hands upon Moses, and sprinkling"|FALSE
626|"about their faces dark waters and thick clouds of the skies, they offer"|FALSE
626|"their heads, unhonoured by the snows of age, for the mitre of the"|FALSE
626|"pontificate. This pest is greatly encouraged, and they are helped to"|FALSE
626|"attain this fantastic clericate with such nimble steps, by Papal"|FALSE
626|"provisions obtained by insidious prayers, and also by the prayers,"|FALSE
626|"which may not be rejected, of cardinals and great men, by the cupidity"|FALSE
626|"of friends and relatives, who, building up Sion in blood, secure"|FALSE
626|"ecclesiastical dignities for their nephews and pupils, before they are"|FALSE
626|"seasoned by the course of nature or ripeness of learning."|FALSE
626|"Alas! by the same disease which we are deploring, we see that the"|FALSE
626|"Palladium of Paris has been carried off in these sad times of ours,"|FALSE
626|"wherein the zeal of that noble university, whose rays once shed light"|FALSE
626|"into every corner of the world, has grown lukewarm, nay, is all but"|FALSE
626|"frozen.  There the pen of every scribe is now at rest, generations of"|FALSE
626|"books no longer succeed each other, and there is none who begins to"|FALSE
626|"take place as a new author.  They wrap up their doctrines in unskilled"|FALSE
626|"discourse, and are losing all propriety of logic, except that our"|FALSE
626|"English subtleties, which they denounce in public, are the subject of"|FALSE
626|"their furtive vigils."|FALSE
626|"Admirable Minerva seems to bend her course to all the nations of the"|FALSE
626|"earth, and reacheth from end to end mightily, that she may reveal"|FALSE
626|"herself to all mankind.  We see that she has already visited the"|FALSE
626|"Indians, the Babylonians, the Egyptians and Greeks, the Arabs and the"|FALSE
626|"Romans.  Now she has passed by Paris, and now has happily come to"|FALSE
626|"Britain, the most noble of islands, nay, rather a microcosm in itself,"|FALSE
626|"that she may show herself a debtor both to the Greeks and to the"|FALSE
626|"Barbarians.  At which wondrous sight it is conceived by most men, that"|FALSE
626|"as philosophy is now lukewarm in France, so her soldiery are unmanned"|FALSE
626|"and languishing."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER X"|FALSE
626|"OF THE GRADUAL PERFECTING OF BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"While assiduously seeking out the wisdom of the men of old, according"|FALSE
626|"to the counsel of the Wise Man (Eccles. xxxix.):  The wise man, he"|FALSE
626|"says, will seek out the wisdom of all the ancients, we have not thought"|FALSE
626|"fit to be misled into the opinion that the first founders of the arts"|FALSE
626|"have purged away all crudeness, knowing that the discoveries of each of"|FALSE
626|"the faithful, when weighed in a faithful balance, makes a tiny portion"|FALSE
626|"of science, but that by the anxious investigations of a multitude of"|FALSE
626|"scholars, each as it were contributing his share, the mighty bodies of"|FALSE
626|"the sciences have grown by successive augmentations to the immense bulk"|FALSE
626|"that we now behold.  For the disciples, continually melting down the"|FALSE
626|"doctrines of their masters, and passing them again through the furnace,"|FALSE
626|"drove off the dross that had been previously overlooked, until there"|FALSE
626|"came out refined gold tried in a furnace of earth, purified seven times"|FALSE
626|"to perfection, and stained by no admixture of error or doubt."|FALSE
626|"For not even Aristotle, although a man of gigantic intellect, in whom"|FALSE
626|"it pleased Nature to try how much of reason she could bestow upon"|FALSE
626|"mortality, and whom the Most High made only a little lower than the"|FALSE
626|"angels, sucked from his own fingers those wonderful volumes which the"|FALSE
626|"whole world can hardly contain.  But, on the contrary, with lynx-eyed"|FALSE
626|"penetration he had seen through the sacred books of the Hebrews, the"|FALSE
626|"Babylonians, the Egyptians, the Chaldaeans, the Persians and the Medes,"|FALSE
626|"all of which learned Greece had transferred into her treasuries.  Whose"|FALSE
626|"true sayings he received, but smoothed away their crudities, pruned"|FALSE
626|"their superfluities, supplied their deficiencies, and removed their"|FALSE
626|"errors.  And he held that we should give thanks not only to those who"|FALSE
626|"teach rightly, but even to those who err, as affording the way of more"|FALSE
626|"easily investigating truth, as he plainly declares in the second book"|FALSE
626|"of his Metaphysics.  Thus many learned lawyers contributed to the"|FALSE
626|"Pandects, many physicians to the Tegni, and it was by this means that"|FALSE
626|"Avicenna edited his Canon, and Pliny his great work on Natural History,"|FALSE
626|"and Ptolemy the Almagest."|FALSE
626|"For as in the writers of annals it is not difficult to see that the"|FALSE
626|"later writer always presupposes the earlier, without whom he could by"|FALSE
626|"no means relate the former times, so too we are to think of the authors"|FALSE
626|"of the sciences.  For no man by himself has brought forth any science,"|FALSE
626|"since between the earliest students and those of the latter time we"|FALSE
626|"find intermediaries, ancient if they be compared with our own age, but"|FALSE
626|"modern if we think of the foundations of learning, and these men we"|FALSE
626|"consider the most learned.  What would Virgil, the chief poet among the"|FALSE
626|"Latins, have achieved, if he had not despoiled Theocritus, Lucretius,"|FALSE
626|"and Homer, and had not ploughed with their heifer?  What, unless again"|FALSE
626|"and again he had read somewhat of Parthenius and Pindar, whose"|FALSE
626|"eloquence he could by no means imitate?  What could Sallust, Tully,"|FALSE
626|"Boethius, Macrobius, Lactantius, Martianus, and in short the whole"|FALSE
626|"troop of Latin writers have done, if they had not seen the productions"|FALSE
626|"of Athens or the volumes of the Greeks?  Certes, little would Jerome,"|FALSE
626|"master of three languages, Ambrosius, Augustine, though he confesses"|FALSE
626|"that he hated Greek, or even Gregory, who is said to have been wholly"|FALSE
626|"ignorant of it, have contributed to the doctrine of the Church, if more"|FALSE
626|"learned Greece had not furnished them from its stores.  As Rome,"|FALSE
626|"watered by the streams of Greece, had earlier brought forth"|FALSE
626|"philosophers in the image of the Greeks, in like fashion afterwards it"|FALSE
626|"produced doctors of the orthodox faith.  The creeds we chant are the"|FALSE
626|"sweat of Grecian brows, promulgated by their Councils, and established"|FALSE
626|"by the martyrdom of many."|FALSE
626|"Yet their natural slowness, as it happens, turns to the glory of the"|FALSE
626|"Latins, since as they were less learned in their studies, so they were"|FALSE
626|"less perverse in their errors.  In truth, the Arian heresy had all but"|FALSE
626|"eclipsed the whole Church; the Nestorian wickedness presumed to rave"|FALSE
626|"with blasphemous rage against the Virgin, for it would have robbed the"|FALSE
626|"Queen of Heaven, not in open fight but in disputation, of her name and"|FALSE
626|"character as Mother of God, unless the invincible champion Cyril, ready"|FALSE
626|"to do single battle, with the help of the Council of Ephesus, had in"|FALSE
626|"vehemence of spirit utterly extinguished it.  Innumerable are the forms"|FALSE
626|"as well as the authors of Greek heresies; for as they were the original"|FALSE
626|"cultivators of our holy faith, so too they were the first sowers of"|FALSE
626|"tares, as is shown by veracious history.  And thus they went on from"|FALSE
626|"bad to worse, because in endeavouring to part the seamless vesture of"|FALSE
626|"the Lord, they totally destroyed primitive simplicity of doctrine, and"|FALSE
626|"blinded by the darkness of novelty would fall into the bottomless pit,"|FALSE
626|"unless He provide for them in His inscrutable prerogative, whose wisdom"|FALSE
626|"is past reckoning."|FALSE
626|"Let this suffice; for here we reach the limit of our power of judgment."|FALSE
626|"One thing, however, we conclude from the premises, that the ignorance"|FALSE
626|"of the Greek tongue is now a great hindrance to the study of the Latin"|FALSE
626|"writers, since without it the doctrines of the ancient authors, whether"|FALSE
626|"Christian or Gentile, cannot be understood.  And we must come to a like"|FALSE
626|"judgment as to Arabic in numerous astronomical treatises, and as to"|FALSE
626|"Hebrew as regards the text of the Holy Bible, which deficiencies,"|FALSE
626|"indeed, Clement V.  provides for, if only the bishops would faithfully"|FALSE
626|"observe what they so lightly decree.  Wherefore we have taken care to"|FALSE
626|"provide a Greek as well as a Hebrew grammar for our scholars, with"|FALSE
626|"certain other aids, by the help of which studious readers may greatly"|FALSE
626|"inform themselves in the writing, reading, and understanding of the"|FALSE
626|"said tongues, although only the hearing of them can teach correctness"|FALSE
626|"of idiom."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XI"|FALSE
626|"WHY WE HAVE PREFERRED BOOKS OF LIBERAL LEARNING TO BOOKS OF LAW"|FALSE
626|"That lucrative practice of positive law, designed for the dispensation"|FALSE
626|"of earthly things, the more useful it is found by the children of this"|FALSE
626|"world, so much the less does it aid the children of light in"|FALSE
626|"comprehending the mysteries of holy writ and the secret sacraments of"|FALSE
626|"the faith, seeing that it disposes us peculiarly to the friendship of"|FALSE
626|"the world, by which man, as S.  James testifies, is made the enemy of"|FALSE
626|"God.  Law indeed encourages rather than extinguishes the contentions of"|FALSE
626|"mankind, which are the result of unbounded greed, by complicated laws,"|FALSE
626|"which can be turned either way; though we know that it was created by"|FALSE
626|"jurisconsults and pious princes for the purpose of assuaging these"|FALSE
626|"contentions.  But in truth, as the same science deals with contraries,"|FALSE
626|"and the power of reason can be used to opposite ends, and at the same"|FALSE
626|"the human mind is more inclined to evil, it happens with the practisers"|FALSE
626|"of this science that they usually devote themselves to promoting"|FALSE
626|"contention rather than peace, and instead of quoting laws according to"|FALSE
626|"the intent of the legislator, violently strain the language thereof to"|FALSE
626|"effect their own purposes."|FALSE
626|"Wherefore, although the over-mastering love of books has possessed our"|FALSE
626|"mind from boyhood, and to rejoice in their delights has been our only"|FALSE
626|"pleasure, yet the appetite for the books of the civil law took less"|FALSE
626|"hold of our affections, and we have spent but little labour and expense"|FALSE
626|"in acquiring volumes of this kind.  For they are useful only as the"|FALSE
626|"scorpion in treacle, as Aristotle, the sun of science, has said of"|FALSE
626|"logic in his book De Pomo.  We have noticed a certain manifest"|FALSE
626|"difference of nature between law and science, in that every science is"|FALSE
626|"delighted and desires to open its inward parts and display the very"|FALSE
626|"heart of its principles, and to show forth the roots from which it buds"|FALSE
626|"and flourishes, and that the emanation of its springs may be seen of"|FALSE
626|"all men; for thus from the cognate and harmonious light of the truth of"|FALSE
626|"conclusion  to principles, the whole body of science will be full of"|FALSE
626|"light, having no part dark.  But laws, on the contrary, since they are"|FALSE
626|"only human enactments for the regulation of social life, or the yokes"|FALSE
626|"of princes thrown over the necks of their subjects, refuse to be"|FALSE
626|"brought to the standard of synteresis, the origin of equity, because"|FALSE
626|"they feel that they possess more of arbitrary will than rational"|FALSE
626|"judgment.  Wherefore the judgment of the wise for the most part is that"|FALSE
626|"the causes of laws are not a fit subject of discussion.  In truth, many"|FALSE
626|"laws acquire force by mere custom, not by syllogistic necessity, like"|FALSE
626|"the arts: as Aristotle, the Phoebus of the Schools, urges in the second"|FALSE
626|"book of the Politics, where he confutes the policy of Hippodamus, which"|FALSE
626|"holds out rewards to the inventors of new laws, because to abrogate old"|FALSE
626|"laws and establish new ones is to weaken the force of those which"|FALSE
626|"exist.  For whatever receives its stability from use alone must"|FALSE
626|"necessarily be brought to nought by disuse."|FALSE
626|"From which it is seen clearly enough, that as laws are neither arts nor"|FALSE
626|"sciences, so books of law cannot properly be called books of art or"|FALSE
626|"science.  Nor is this faculty which we may call by a special term"|FALSE
626|"geologia, or the earthly science, to be properly numbered among the"|FALSE
626|"sciences.  Now the books of the liberal arts are so useful to the"|FALSE
626|"divine writings, that without their aid the intellect would vainly"|FALSE
626|"aspire to understand them."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XII"|FALSE
626|"WHY WE HAVE CAUSED BOOKS OF GRAMMAR TO BE SO DILIGENTLY PREPARED"|FALSE
626|"While we were constantly delighting ourselves with the reading of"|FALSE
626|"books, which it was our custom to read or have read to us every day, we"|FALSE
626|"noticed plainly how much the defective knowledge even of a single word"|FALSE
626|"hinders the understanding, as the meaning of no sentence can be"|FALSE
626|"apprehended, if any part of it be not understood.  Wherefore we ordered"|FALSE
626|"the meanings of foreign words to be noted with particular care, and"|FALSE
626|"studied the orthography, prosody, etymology, and syntax in ancient"|FALSE
626|"grammarians with unrelaxing carefulness, and took pains to elucidate"|FALSE
626|"terms that had grown too obscure by age with suitable explanations, in"|FALSE
626|"order to make a smooth path for our students."|FALSE
626|"This is the whole reason why we took care to replace the antiquated"|FALSE
626|"volumes of the grammarians by improved codices, that we might make"|FALSE
626|"royal roads, by which our scholars in time to come might attain without"|FALSE
626|"stumbling to any science."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XIII"|FALSE
626|"WHY WE HAVE NOT WHOLLY NEGLECTED THE FABLES OF THE POETS"|FALSE
626|"All the varieties of attack directed against the poets by the lovers of"|FALSE
626|"naked truth may be repelled by a two-fold defence: either that even in"|FALSE
626|"an unseemly subject-matter we may learn a charming fashion of speech,"|FALSE
626|"or that where a fictitious but becoming subject is handled, natural or"|FALSE
626|"historical truth is pursued under the guise of allegorical fiction."|FALSE
626|"Although it is true that all men naturally desire knowledge, yet they"|FALSE
626|"do not all take the same pleasure in learning.  On the contrary, when"|FALSE
626|"they have experienced the labour of study and find their senses"|FALSE
626|"wearied, most men inconsiderately fling away the nut, before they have"|FALSE
626|"broken the shell and reached the kernel.  For man is naturally fond of"|FALSE
626|"two things, namely, freedom from control and some pleasure in his"|FALSE
626|"activity; for which reason no one without reason submits himself to the"|FALSE
626|"control of others, or willingly engages in any tedious task.  For"|FALSE
626|"pleasure crowns activity, as beauty is a crown to youth, as Aristotle"|FALSE
626|"truly asserts in the tenth book of the Ethics.  Accordingly the wisdom"|FALSE
626|"of the ancients devised a remedy by which to entice the wanton minds of"|FALSE
626|"men by a kind of pious fraud, the delicate Minerva secretly lurking"|FALSE
626|"beneath the mask of pleasure.  We are wont to allure children by"|FALSE
626|"rewards, that they may cheerfully learn what we force them to study"|FALSE
626|"even though they are unwilling.  For our fallen nature does not tend to"|FALSE
626|"virtue with the same enthusiasm with which it rushes into vice.  Horace"|FALSE
626|"has expressed this for us in a brief verse of the Ars Poetica, where he"|FALSE
626|"says:"|FALSE
626|"  All poets sing to profit or delight."|FALSE
626|"And he has plainly intimated the same thing in another verse of the"|FALSE
626|"same book, where he says:"|FALSE
626|"     He hits the mark, who mingles joy with use."|FALSE
626|"How many students of Euclid have been repelled by the Pons Asinorum, as"|FALSE
626|"by a lofty and precipitous rock, which no help of ladders could enable"|FALSE
626|"them to scale!  THIS IS A HARD SAYING, they exclaim, AND WHO CAN"|FALSE
626|"RECEIVE IT.  The child of inconstancy, who ended by wishing to be"|FALSE
626|"transformed into an ass, would perhaps never have given up the study of"|FALSE
626|"philosophy, if he had met him in friendly guise veiled under the cloak"|FALSE
626|"of pleasure; but anon, astonished by Crato's chair and struck dumb by"|FALSE
626|"his endless questions, as by a sudden thunderbolt, he saw no refuge but"|FALSE
626|"in flight."|FALSE
626|"So much we have alleged in defence of the poets; and now we proceed to"|FALSE
626|"show that those who study them with proper intent are not to be"|FALSE
626|"condemned in regard to them.  For our ignorance of one single word"|FALSE
626|"prevents the understanding of a whole long sentence, as was assumed in"|FALSE
626|"the previous chapter.  As now the sayings of the saints frequently"|FALSE
626|"allude to the inventions of the poets, it must needs happen that"|FALSE
626|"through our not knowing the poem referred to, the whole meaning of the"|FALSE
626|"author is completely obscured, and assuredly, as Cassiodorus says in"|FALSE
626|"his book Of the Institutes of Sacred Literature:  Those things are not"|FALSE
626|"to be considered trifles without which great things cannot come to"|FALSE
626|"pass.  It follows therefore that through ignorance of poetry we do not"|FALSE
626|"understand Jerome, Augustine, Boethius, Lactantius, Sidonius, and very"|FALSE
626|"many others, a catalogue of whom would more than fill a long chapter."|FALSE
626|"The Venerable Bede has very clearly discussed and determined this"|FALSE
626|"doubtful point, as is related by that great compiler Gratian, the"|FALSE
626|"repeater of numerous authors, who is as confused in form as he was"|FALSE
626|"eager in collecting matter for his compilation.  Now he writes in his"|FALSE
626|"37th section:  Some read secular literature for pleasure, taking"|FALSE
626|"delight in the inventions and elegant language of the poets; but others"|FALSE
626|"study this literature for the sake of scholarship, that by their"|FALSE
626|"reading they may learn to detest the errors of the Gentiles and may"|FALSE
626|"devoutly apply what they find useful in them to the use of sacred"|FALSE
626|"learning.  Such men study secular literature in a laudable manner. So"|FALSE
626|"far Bede."|FALSE
626|"Taking this salutary instruction to heart, let the detractors of those"|FALSE
626|"who study the poets henceforth hold their peace, and let not those who"|FALSE
626|"are ignorant of these things require that others should be as ignorant"|FALSE
626|"as themselves, for this is the consolation of the wretched.  And"|FALSE
626|"therefore let every man see that his own intentions are upright, and he"|FALSE
626|"may thus make of any subject, observing the limitations of virtue, a"|FALSE
626|"study acceptable to God.  And if he have found profit in poetry, as the"|FALSE
626|"great Virgil relates that he had done in Ennius, he will not have done"|FALSE
626|"amiss."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XIV"|FALSE
626|"WHO OUGHT TO BE SPECIAL LOVERS OF BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"To him who recollects what has been said before, it is plain and"|FALSE
626|"evident who ought to be the chief lovers of books.  For those who have"|FALSE
626|"most need of wisdom in order to perform usefully the duties of their"|FALSE
626|"position, they are without doubt most especially bound to show more"|FALSE
626|"abundantly to the sacred vessels of wisdom the anxious affection of a"|FALSE
626|"grateful heart.  Now it is the office of the wise man to order rightly"|FALSE
626|"both himself and others, according to the Phoebus of philosophers,"|FALSE
626|"Aristotle, who deceives not nor is deceived in human things.  Wherefore"|FALSE
626|"princes and prelates, judges and doctors, and all other leaders of the"|FALSE
626|"commonwealth, as more than others they have need of wisdom, so more"|FALSE
626|"than others ought they to show zeal for the vessels of wisdom."|FALSE
626|"Boethius, indeed, beheld Philosophy bearing a sceptre in her left hand"|FALSE
626|"and books in her right, by which it is evidently shown to all men that"|FALSE
626|"no one can rightly rule a commonwealth without books. Thou, says"|FALSE
626|"Boethius, speaking to Philosophy, hast sanctioned this saying by the"|FALSE
626|"mouth of Plato, that states would be happy if they were ruled by"|FALSE
626|"students of philosophy, or if their rulers would study philosophy.  And"|FALSE
626|"again, we are taught by the very gesture of the figure that in so far"|FALSE
626|"as the right hand is better than the left, so far the contemplative"|FALSE
626|"life is more worthy than the active life; and at the same time we are"|FALSE
626|"shown that the business of the wise man is to devote himself by turns,"|FALSE
626|"now to the study of truth, and now to the dispensation of temporal"|FALSE
626|"things."|FALSE
626|"We read that Philip thanked the Gods devoutly for having granted that"|FALSE
626|"Alexander should be born in the time of Aristotle, so that educated"|FALSE
626|"under his instruction he might be worthy to rule his father's empire."|FALSE
626|"While Phaeton unskilled in driving becomes the charioteer of his"|FALSE
626|"father's car, he unhappily distributes to mankind the heat of Phoebus,"|FALSE
626|"now by excessive nearness, and now by withdrawing it too far, and so,"|FALSE
626|"lest all beneath him should be imperilled by the closeness of his"|FALSE
626|"driving, justly deserved to be struck by the thunderbolt."|FALSE
626|"The history of the Greeks as well as Romans shows that there were no"|FALSE
626|"famous princes among them who were devoid of literature.  The sacred"|FALSE
626|"law of Moses in prescribing to the king a rule of government, enjoins"|FALSE
626|"him to have a copy made of the book of Divine law (Deut. xvii.)"|FALSE
626|"according to the copy shown by the priests, in which he was to read all"|FALSE
626|"the days of his life.  Certes, God Himself, who hath made and who"|FALSE
626|"fashioneth every day the hearts of every one of us, knows the"|FALSE
626|"feebleness of human memory and the instability of virtuous intentions"|FALSE
626|"in mankind.  Wherefore He has willed that books should be as it were an"|FALSE
626|"antidote to all evil, the reading and use of which He has commanded to"|FALSE
626|"be the healthful daily nourishment of the soul, so that by them the"|FALSE
626|"intellect being refreshed and neither weak nor doubtful should never"|FALSE
626|"hesitate in action.  This subject is elegantly handled by John of"|FALSE
626|"Salisbury, in his Policraticon.  In conclusion, all classes of men who"|FALSE
626|"are conspicuous by the tonsure or the sign of clerkship, against whom"|FALSE
626|"books lifted up their voices in the fourth, fifth, and sixth chapters,"|FALSE
626|"are bound to serve books with perpetual veneration."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XV"|FALSE
626|"OF THE ADVANTAGES OF THE LOVE OF BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"It transcends the power of human intellect, however deeply it may have"|FALSE
626|"drunk of the Pegasean fount, to develop fully the title of the present"|FALSE
626|"chapter.  Though one should speak with the tongue of men and angels,"|FALSE
626|"though he should become a Mercury or Tully, though he should grow sweet"|FALSE
626|"with the milky eloquence of Livy, yet he will plead the stammering of"|FALSE
626|"Moses, or with Jeremiah will confess that he is but a boy and cannot"|FALSE
626|"speak, or will imitate Echo rebounding from the mountains.  For we know"|FALSE
626|"that the love of books is the same thing as the love of wisdom, as was"|FALSE
626|"proved in the second chapter.  Now this love is called by the Greek"|FALSE
626|"word philosophy, the whole virtue of which no created intelligence can"|FALSE
626|"comprehend; for she is believed to be the mother of all good things:"|FALSE
626|"Wisdom vii.  She as a heavenly dew extinguishes the heats of fleshly"|FALSE
626|"vices, the intense activity of the mental forces relaxing the vigour of"|FALSE
626|"the animal forces, and slothfulness being wholly put to flight, which"|FALSE
626|"being gone all the bows of Cupid are unstrung."|FALSE
626|"Hence Plato says in the Phaedo:  The philosopher is manifest in this,"|FALSE
626|"that he dissevers the soul from communion with the body.  Love, says"|FALSE
626|"Jerome, the knowledge of the scriptures, and thou wilt not love the"|FALSE
626|"vices of the flesh.  The godlike Xenocrates showed this by the firmness"|FALSE
626|"of his reason, who was declared by the famous hetaera Phryne to be a"|FALSE
626|"statue and not a man, when all her blandishments could not shake his"|FALSE
626|"resolve, as Valerius Maximus relates at length.  Our own Origen showed"|FALSE
626|"this also, who chose rather to be unsexed by the mutilation of himself,"|FALSE
626|"than to be made effeminate by the omnipotence of woman--though it was a"|FALSE
626|"hasty remedy, repugnant alike to nature and to virtue, whose place it"|FALSE
626|"is not to make men insensible to passion, but to slay with the dagger"|FALSE
626|"of reason the passions that spring from instinct."|FALSE
626|"Again, all who are smitten with the love of books think cheaply of the"|FALSE
626|"world and wealth; as Jerome says to Vigilantius:  The same man cannot"|FALSE
626|"love both gold and books.  And thus it has been said in verse:"|FALSE
626|"  No iron-stained hand is fit to handle books,"|FALSE
626|"  Nor he whose heart on gold so gladly looks:"|FALSE
626|"  The same men love not books and money both,"|FALSE
626|"  And books thy herd, O Epicurus, loathe;"|FALSE
626|"  Misers and bookmen make poor company,"|FALSE
626|"  Nor dwell in peace beneath the same roof-tree."|FALSE
626|"  No man, therefore, can serve both books and Mammon."|FALSE
626|"The hideousness of vice is greatly reprobated in books, so that he who"|FALSE
626|"loves to commune with books is led to detest all manner of vice.  The"|FALSE
626|"demon, who derives his name from knowledge, is most effectually"|FALSE
626|"defeated by the knowledge of books, and through books his multitudinous"|FALSE
626|"deceits and the endless labyrinths of his guile are laid bare to those"|FALSE
626|"who read, lest he be transformed into an angel of light and circumvent"|FALSE
626|"the innocent by his wiles.  The reverence of God is revealed to us by"|FALSE
626|"books, the virtues by which He is worshipped are more expressly"|FALSE
626|"manifested, and the rewards are described that are promised by the"|FALSE
626|"truth, which deceives not, neither is deceived.  The truest likeness of"|FALSE
626|"the beatitude to come is the contemplation of the sacred writings, in"|FALSE
626|"which we behold in turn the Creator and the creature, and draw from"|FALSE
626|"streams of perpetual gladness.  Faith is established by the power of"|FALSE
626|"books; hope is strengthened by their solace, insomuch that by patience"|FALSE
626|"and the consolation of scripture we are in good hope.  Charity is not"|FALSE
626|"puffed up, but is edified by the knowledge of true learning, and,"|FALSE
626|"indeed, it is clearer than light that the Church is established upon"|FALSE
626|"the sacred writings."|FALSE
626|"Books delight us, when prosperity smiles upon us; they comfort us"|FALSE
626|"inseparably when stormy fortune frowns on us.  They lend validity to"|FALSE
626|"human compacts, and no serious judgments are propounded without their"|FALSE
626|"help.  Arts and sciences, all the advantages of which no mind can"|FALSE
626|"enumerate, consist in books.  How highly must we estimate the wondrous"|FALSE
626|"power of books, since through them we survey the utmost bounds of the"|FALSE
626|"world and time, and contemplate the things that are as well as those"|FALSE
626|"that are not, as it were in the mirror of eternity.  In books we climb"|FALSE
626|"mountains and scan the deepest gulfs of the abyss; in books we behold"|FALSE
626|"the finny tribes that may not exist outside their native waters,"|FALSE
626|"distinguish the properties of streams and springs and of various lands;"|FALSE
626|"from books we dig out gems and metals and the materials of every kind"|FALSE
626|"of mineral, and learn the virtues of herbs and trees and plants, and"|FALSE
626|"survey at will the whole progeny of Neptune, Ceres, and Pluto."|FALSE
626|"But if we please to visit the heavenly inhabitants, Taurus, Caucasus,"|FALSE
626|"and Olympus are at hand, from which we pass beyond the realms of Juno"|FALSE
626|"and mark out the territories of the seven planets by lines and circles."|FALSE
626|"And finally we traverse the loftiest firmament of all, adorned with"|FALSE
626|"signs, degrees, and figures in the utmost variety.  There we inspect"|FALSE
626|"the antarctic pole, which eye hath not seen, nor ear heard; we admire"|FALSE
626|"the luminous Milky Way and the Zodiac, marvellously and delightfully"|FALSE
626|"pictured with celestial animals.  Thence by books we pass on to"|FALSE
626|"separate substances, that the intellect may greet kindred"|FALSE
626|"intelligences, and with the mind's eye may discern the First Cause of"|FALSE
626|"all things and the Unmoved Mover of infinite virtue, and may immerse"|FALSE
626|"itself in love without end.  See how with the aid of books we attain"|FALSE
626|"the reward of our beatitude, while we are yet sojourners below."|FALSE
626|"Why need we say more?  Certes, just as we have learnt on the authority"|FALSE
626|"of Seneca, leisure without letters is death and the sepulture of the"|FALSE
626|"living, so contrariwise we conclude that occupation with letters or"|FALSE
626|"books is the life of man."|FALSE
626|"Again, by means of books we communicate to friends as well as foes what"|FALSE
626|"we cannot safely entrust to messengers; since the book is generally"|FALSE
626|"allowed access to the chambers of princes, from which the voice of its"|FALSE
626|"author would be rigidly excluded, as Tertullian observes at the"|FALSE
626|"beginning of his Apologeticus.  When shut up in prison and in bonds,"|FALSE
626|"and utterly deprived of bodily liberty, we use books as ambassadors to"|FALSE
626|"our friends, and entrust them with the conduct of our cause, and send"|FALSE
626|"them where to go ourselves would incur the penalty of death.  By the"|FALSE
626|"aid of books we remember things that are past, and even prophesy as to"|FALSE
626|"the future; and things present, which shift and flow, we perpetuate by"|FALSE
626|"committing them to writing."|FALSE
626|"The felicitous studiousness and the studious felicity of the"|FALSE
626|"all-powerful eunuch, of whom we are told in the Acts, who had been so"|FALSE
626|"mightily kindled by the love of the prophetic writings that he ceased"|FALSE
626|"not from his reading by reason of his journey, had banished all thought"|FALSE
626|"of the populous palace of Queen Candace, and had forgotten even the"|FALSE
626|"treasures of which he was the keeper, and had neglected alike his"|FALSE
626|"journey and the chariot in which he rode.  Love of his book alone had"|FALSE
626|"wholly engrossed this domicile of chastity, under whose guidance he"|FALSE
626|"soon deserved to enter the gate of faith.  O gracious love of books,"|FALSE
626|"which by the grace of baptism transformed the child of Gehenna and"|FALSE
626|"nursling of Tartarus into a Son of the Kingdom!"|FALSE
626|"Let the feeble pen now cease from the tenor of an infinite task, lest"|FALSE
626|"it seem foolishly to undertake what in the beginning it confessed to be"|FALSE
626|"impossible to any."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XVI"|FALSE
626|"THAT IT IS MERITORIOUS TO WRITE NEW BOOKS AND TO RENEW THE OLD"|FALSE
626|"Just as it is necessary for the state to prepare arms and to provide"|FALSE
626|"abundant stores of victuals for the soldiers who are to fight for it,"|FALSE
626|"so it is fitting for the Church Militant to fortify itself against the"|FALSE
626|"assaults of pagans and heretics with a multitude of sound writings."|FALSE
626|"But because all the appliances of mortal men with the lapse of time"|FALSE
626|"suffer the decay of mortality, it is needful to replace the volumes"|FALSE
626|"that are worn out with age by fresh successors, that the perpetuity of"|FALSE
626|"which the individual is by its nature incapable may be secured to the"|FALSE
626|"species; and hence it is that the Preacher says: Of making many books"|FALSE
626|"there is no end.  For as the bodies of books, seeing that they are"|FALSE
626|"formed of a combination of contrary elements, undergo a continual"|FALSE
626|"dissolution of their structure, so by the forethought of the clergy a"|FALSE
626|"remedy should be found, by means of which the sacred book paying the"|FALSE
626|"debt of nature may obtain a natural heir and may raise up like seed to"|FALSE
626|"its dead brother, and thus may be verified that saying of"|FALSE
626|"Ecclesiasticus: His father is dead, and he is as if he were not dead;"|FALSE
626|"for he hath left one behind him that is like himself.  And thus the"|FALSE
626|"transcription of ancient books is as it were the begetting of fresh"|FALSE
626|"sons, on whom the office of the father may devolve, lest it suffer"|FALSE
626|"detriment.  Now such transcribers are called antiquarii, whose"|FALSE
626|"occupations Cassiodorus confesses please him above all the tasks of"|FALSE
626|"bodily labour, adding: \"Happy effort,\" he says, \"laudable industry, to"|FALSE
626|"preach to men with the hand, to let loose tongues with the fingers,"|FALSE
626|"silently to give salvation to mortals, and to fight with pen and ink"|FALSE
626|"against the illicit wiles of the Evil One.\"  So far Cassiodorus."|FALSE
626|"Moreover, our Saviour exercised the office of the scribe when He"|FALSE
626|"stooped down and with His finger wrote on the ground (John viii.), that"|FALSE
626|"no one, however exalted, may think it unworthy of him to do what he"|FALSE
626|"sees the wisdom of God the Father did."|FALSE
626|"O singular serenity of writing, to practise which the Artificer of the"|FALSE
626|"world stoops down, at whose dread name every knee doth bow!  O"|FALSE
626|"venerable handicraft pre-eminent above all other crafts that are"|FALSE
626|"practised by the hand of man, to which our Lord humbly inclines His"|FALSE
626|"breast, to which the finger of God is applied, performing the office of"|FALSE
626|"a pen!  We do not read of the Son of God that He sowed or ploughed,"|FALSE
626|"wove or digged; nor did any other of the mechanic arts befit the divine"|FALSE
626|"wisdom incarnate except to trace letters in writing, that every"|FALSE
626|"gentleman and sciolist may know that fingers are given by God to men"|FALSE
626|"for the task of writing rather than for war.  Wherefore we entirely"|FALSE
626|"approve the judgment of books, wherein they declared in our sixth"|FALSE
626|"chapter the clerk who cannot write to be as it were disabled."|FALSE
626|"God himself inscribes the just in the book of the living; Moses"|FALSE
626|"received the tables of stone written with the finger of God.  Job"|FALSE
626|"desires that he himself that judgeth would write a book.  Belshazzar"|FALSE
626|"trembled when he saw the fingers of a man's hand writing upon the wall,"|FALSE
626|"Mene tekel phares.  I wrote, says Jeremiah, with ink in the book."|FALSE
626|"Christ bids his beloved disciple John, What thou seest write in a book."|FALSE
626|"So the office of the writer is enjoined on Isaiah and on Joshua, that"|FALSE
626|"the act and skill of writing may be commended to future generations."|FALSE
626|"Christ Himself has written on His vesture and on His thigh King of"|FALSE
626|"Kings and Lord of Lords, so that without writing the royal ornaments of"|FALSE
626|"the Omnipotent cannot be made perfect.  Being dead they cease not to"|FALSE
626|"teach, who write books of sacred learning.  Paul did more for building"|FALSE
626|"up the fabric of the Church by writing his holy epistles, than by"|FALSE
626|"preaching by word of mouth to Jews and Gentiles.  He who has attained"|FALSE
626|"the prize continues daily by books, what he long ago began while a"|FALSE
626|"sojourner upon the earth; and thus is fulfilled in the doctors writing"|FALSE
626|"books the saying of the Prophet:  They that turn many to righteousness"|FALSE
626|"shall be as the stars for ever and ever."|FALSE
626|"Moreover, it has been determined by the doctors of the Church that the"|FALSE
626|"longevity of the ancients, before God destroyed the original world by"|FALSE
626|"the Deluge, is to be ascribed to a miracle and not to nature; as though"|FALSE
626|"God granted to them such length of days as was required for finding out"|FALSE
626|"the sciences and writing them in books; amongst which the wonderful"|FALSE
626|"variety of astronomy required, according to Josephus, a period of six"|FALSE
626|"hundred years, to submit it to ocular observation.  Nor, indeed, do"|FALSE
626|"they deny that the fruits of the earth in that primitive age afforded a"|FALSE
626|"more nutritious aliment to men than in our modern times, and thus they"|FALSE
626|"had not only a livelier energy of body, but also a more lengthened"|FALSE
626|"period of vigour; to which it contributed not a little that they lived"|FALSE
626|"according to virtue and denied themselves all luxurious delights."|FALSE
626|"Whoever therefore is by the good gift of God endowed with gift of"|FALSE
626|"science, let him, according to the counsel of the Holy Spirit, write"|FALSE
626|"wisdom in his time of leisure (Eccles.  xxxviii.), that his reward may"|FALSE
626|"be with the blessed and his days may be lengthened in this present"|FALSE
626|"world."|FALSE
626|"And further, if we turn our discourse to the princes of the world, we"|FALSE
626|"find that famous emperors not only attained excellent skill in the art"|FALSE
626|"of writing, but indulged greatly in its practice.  Julius Caesar, the"|FALSE
626|"first and greatest of them all, has left us Commentaries on the Gallic"|FALSE
626|"and the Civil Wars written by himself; he wrote also two books De"|FALSE
626|"Analogia, and two books of Anticatones, and a poem called Iter; and"|FALSE
626|"many other works.  Julius and Augustus devised means of writing one"|FALSE
626|"letter for another, and so concealing what they wrote.  For Julius put"|FALSE
626|"the fourth letter for the first, and so on through the alphabet; whilst"|FALSE
626|"Augustus used the second for the first, the third for the second, and"|FALSE
626|"so throughout.  He is said in the greatest difficulties of affairs"|FALSE
626|"during the Mutinensian War to have read and written and even declaimed"|FALSE
626|"every day.  Tiberius wrote a lyric poem and some Greek verses."|FALSE
626|"Claudius likewise was skilled in both Greek and Latin, and wrote"|FALSE
626|"several books.  But Titus was skilled above all men in the art of"|FALSE
626|"writing, and easily imitated any hand he chose; so that he used to say"|FALSE
626|"that if he had wished it he might have become a most skilful forger."|FALSE
626|"All these things are noted by Suetonius in his Lives of the XII."|FALSE
626|"Caesars."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XVII"|FALSE
626|"OF SHOWING DUE PROPRIETY IN THE CUSTODY OF BOOKS"|FALSE
626|"We are not only rendering service to God in preparing volumes of new"|FALSE
626|"books, but also exercising an office of sacred piety when we treat"|FALSE
626|"books carefully, and again when we restore them to their proper places"|FALSE
626|"and commend them to inviolable custody; that they may rejoice in purity"|FALSE
626|"while we have them in our hands, and rest securely when they are put"|FALSE
626|"back in their repositories.  And surely next to the vestments and"|FALSE
626|"vessels dedicated to the Lord's body, holy books deserve to be rightly"|FALSE
626|"treated by the clergy, to which great injury is done so often as they"|FALSE
626|"are touched by unclean hands.  Wherefore we deem it expedient to warn"|FALSE
626|"our students of various negligences, which might always be easily"|FALSE
626|"avoided and do wonderful harm to books."|FALSE
626|"And in the first place as to the opening and closing of books, let"|FALSE
626|"there be due moderation, that they be not unclasped in precipitate"|FALSE
626|"haste, nor when we have finished our inspection be put away without"|FALSE
626|"being duly closed.  For it behoves us to guard a book much more"|FALSE
626|"carefully than a boot."|FALSE
626|"But the race of scholars is commonly badly brought up, and unless they"|FALSE
626|"are bridled in by the rules of their elders they indulge in infinite"|FALSE
626|"puerilities.  They behave with petulance, and are puffed up with"|FALSE
626|"presumption, judging of everything as if they were certain, though they"|FALSE
626|"are altogether inexperienced."|FALSE
626|"You may happen to see some headstrong youth lazily lounging over his"|FALSE
626|"studies, and when the winter's frost is sharp, his nose running from"|FALSE
626|"the nipping cold drips down, nor does he think of wiping it with his"|FALSE
626|"pocket-handkerchief until he has bedewed the book before him with the"|FALSE
626|"ugly moisture.  Would that he had before him no book, but a cobbler's"|FALSE
626|"apron!  His nails are stuffed with fetid filth as black as jet, with"|FALSE
626|"which he marks any passage that pleases him.  He distributes a"|FALSE
626|"multitude of straws, which he inserts to stick out in different places,"|FALSE
626|"so that the halm may remind him of what his memory cannot retain."|FALSE
626|"These straws, because the book has no stomach to digest them, and no"|FALSE
626|"one takes them out, first distend the book from its wonted closing, and"|FALSE
626|"at length, being carelessly abandoned to oblivion, go to decay.  He"|FALSE
626|"does not fear to eat fruit or cheese over an open book, or carelessly"|FALSE
626|"to carry a cup to and from his mouth; and because he has no wallet at"|FALSE
626|"hand he drops into books the fragments that are left.  Continually"|FALSE
626|"chattering, he is never weary of disputing with his companions, and"|FALSE
626|"while he alleges a crowd of senseless arguments, he wets the book lying"|FALSE
626|"half open in his lap with sputtering showers.  Aye, and then hastily"|FALSE
626|"folding his arms he leans forward on the book, and by a brief spell of"|FALSE
626|"study invites a prolonged nap; and then, by way of mending the"|FALSE
626|"wrinkles, he folds back the margin of the leaves, to the no small"|FALSE
626|"injury of the book.  Now the rain is over and gone, and the flowers"|FALSE
626|"have appeared in our land.  Then the scholar we are speaking of, a"|FALSE
626|"neglecter rather than an inspecter of books, will stuff his volume with"|FALSE
626|"violets, and primroses, with roses and quatrefoil.  Then he will use"|FALSE
626|"his wet and perspiring hands to turn over the volumes; then he will"|FALSE
626|"thump the white vellum with gloves covered with all kinds of dust, and"|FALSE
626|"with his finger clad in long-used leather will hunt line by line"|FALSE
626|"through the page; then at the sting of the biting flea the sacred book"|FALSE
626|"is flung aside, and is hardly shut for another month, until it is so"|FALSE
626|"full of the dust that has found its way within, that it resists the"|FALSE
626|"effort to close it."|FALSE
626|"But the handling of books is specially to be forbidden to those"|FALSE
626|"shameless youths, who as soon as they have learned to form the shapes"|FALSE
626|"of letters, straightway, if they have the opportunity, become unhappy"|FALSE
626|"commentators, and wherever they find an extra margin about the text,"|FALSE
626|"furnish it with monstrous alphabets, or if any other frivolity strikes"|FALSE
626|"their fancy, at once their pen begins to write it.  There the Latinist"|FALSE
626|"and sophister and every unlearned writer tries the fitness of his pen,"|FALSE
626|"a practice that we have frequently seen injuring the usefulness and"|FALSE
626|"value of the most beautiful books."|FALSE
626|"Again, there is a class of thieves shamefully mutilating books, who cut"|FALSE
626|"away the margins from the sides to use as material for letters, leaving"|FALSE
626|"only the text, or employ the leaves from the ends, inserted for the"|FALSE
626|"protection of the book, for various uses and abuses--a kind of"|FALSE
626|"sacrilege which should be prohibited by the threat of anathema."|FALSE
626|"Again, it is part of the decency of scholars that whenever they return"|FALSE
626|"from meals to their study, washing should invariably precede reading,"|FALSE
626|"and that no grease-stained finger should unfasten the clasps, or turn"|FALSE
626|"the leaves of a book.  Nor let a crying child admire the pictures in"|FALSE
626|"the capital letters, lest he soil the parchment with wet fingers; for a"|FALSE
626|"child instantly touches whatever he sees.  Moreover, the laity, who"|FALSE
626|"look at a book turned upside down just as if it were open in the right"|FALSE
626|"way, are utterly unworthy of any communion with books.  Let the clerk"|FALSE
626|"take care also that the smutty scullion reeking from his stewpots does"|FALSE
626|"not touch the lily leaves of books, all unwashed, but he who walketh"|FALSE
626|"without blemish shall minister to the precious volumes.  And, again,"|FALSE
626|"the cleanliness of decent hands would be of great benefit to books as"|FALSE
626|"well as scholars, if it were not that the itch and pimples are"|FALSE
626|"characteristic of the clergy."|FALSE
626|"Whenever defects are noticed in books, they should be promptly"|FALSE
626|"repaired, since nothing spreads more quickly than a tear and a rent"|FALSE
626|"which is neglected at the time will have to be repaired afterwards with"|FALSE
626|"usury."|FALSE
626|"Moses, the gentlest of men, teaches us to make bookcases most neatly,"|FALSE
626|"wherein they may be protected from any injury: Take, he says, this book"|FALSE
626|"of the law, and put it in the side of the ark of the covenant of the"|FALSE
626|"Lord your God.   O fitting place and appropriate for a library, which"|FALSE
626|"was made of imperishable shittim-wood, and was all covered within and"|FALSE
626|"without with gold!  But the Saviour also has warned us by His example"|FALSE
626|"against all unbecoming carelessness in the handling of books, as we"|FALSE
626|"read in S.  Luke.  For when He had read the scriptural prophecy of"|FALSE
626|"Himself in the book that was delivered to Him, He did not give it again"|FALSE
626|"to the minister, until He had closed it with his own most sacred hands."|FALSE
626|"By which students are most clearly taught that in the care of books the"|FALSE
626|"merest trifles ought not to be neglected."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XVIII"|FALSE
626|"SHOWETH THAT WE HAVE COLLECTED SO GREAT STORE OF BOOKS FOR THE COMMON"|FALSE
626|"BENEFIT OF SCHOLARS AND NOT ONLY FOR OUR OWN PLEASURE"|FALSE
626|"Nothing in human affairs is more unjust than that those things which"|FALSE
626|"are most righteously done, should be perverted by the slanders of"|FALSE
626|"malicious men, and that one should bear the reproach of sin where he"|FALSE
626|"has rather deserved the hope of honour.  Many things are done with"|FALSE
626|"singleness of eye, the right hand knoweth not what the left hand doth,"|FALSE
626|"the lump is uncorrupted by leaven, nor is the garment woven of wool and"|FALSE
626|"linen; and yet by the trickery of perverse men a pious work is"|FALSE
626|"mendaciously transformed into some monstrous act.  Certes, such is the"|FALSE
626|"unhappy condition of sinful nature, that not merely in acts that are"|FALSE
626|"morally doubtful it adopts the worse conclusion; but often it depraves"|FALSE
626|"by iniquitous subversion those which have the appearance of rectitude."|FALSE
626|"For although the love of books from the nature of its object bears the"|FALSE
626|"aspect of goodness, yet, wonderful to say, it has rendered us obnoxious"|FALSE
626|"to the censures of many, by whose astonishment we were disparaged and"|FALSE
626|"censured, now for excess of curiosity, now for the exhibition of"|FALSE
626|"vanity, now for intemperance of delight in literature; though indeed we"|FALSE
626|"were no more disturbed by their vituperation than by the barking of so"|FALSE
626|"many dogs, satisfied with the testimony of Him to whom it appertaineth"|FALSE
626|"to try the hearts and reins.  For as the aim and purpose of our inmost"|FALSE
626|"will is inscrutable to men and is seen of God alone, the searcher of"|FALSE
626|"hearts, they deserve to be rebuked for their pernicious temerity, who"|FALSE
626|"so eagerly set a mark of condemnation upon human acts, the ultimate"|FALSE
626|"springs of which they cannot see.  For the final end in matters of"|FALSE
626|"conduct holds the same position as first principles in speculative"|FALSE
626|"science or axioms in mathematics, as the chief of philosophers,"|FALSE
626|"Aristotle, points out in the seventh book of the Ethics.  And"|FALSE
626|"therefore, just as the truth of our conclusions depends upon the"|FALSE
626|"correctness of our premises, so in matters of action the stamp of moral"|FALSE
626|"rectitude is given by the honesty of aim and purpose, in cases where"|FALSE
626|"the act itself would otherwise be held to be morally indifferent."|FALSE
626|"Now we have long cherished in our heart of hearts the fixed resolve,"|FALSE
626|"when Providence should grant a favourable opportunity, to found in"|FALSE
626|"perpetual charity a Hall in the reverend university of Oxford, the"|FALSE
626|"chief nursing mother of all liberal arts, and to endow it with the"|FALSE
626|"necessary revenues, for the maintenance of a number of scholars; and"|FALSE
626|"moreover to enrich the Hall with the treasures of our books, that all"|FALSE
626|"and every of them should be in common as regards their use and study,"|FALSE
626|"not only to the scholars of the said Hall, but by their means to all"|FALSE
626|"the students of the before-named university for ever, in the form and"|FALSE
626|"manner which the following chapter shall declare.  Wherefore the"|FALSE
626|"sincere love of study and zeal for the strengthening of the orthodox"|FALSE
626|"faith to the edifying of the Church, have begotten in us that"|FALSE
626|"solicitude so marvellous to the lovers of pelf, of collecting books"|FALSE
626|"wherever they were to be purchased, regardless of expense, and of"|FALSE
626|"having those that could not he bought fairly transcribed."|FALSE
626|"For as the favourite occupations of men are variously distinguished"|FALSE
626|"according to the disposition of the heavenly bodies, which frequently"|FALSE
626|"control our natural composition, so that some men choose to devote"|FALSE
626|"themselves to architecture, others to agriculture, others to hunting,"|FALSE
626|"others to navigation, others to war, others to games, we have under the"|FALSE
626|"aspect of Mercury entertained a blameless pleasure in books, which"|FALSE
626|"under the rule of right reason, over which no stars are dominant, we"|FALSE
626|"have ordered to the glory of the Supreme Being, that where our minds"|FALSE
626|"found tranquillity and peace, thence also might spring a most devout"|FALSE
626|"service of God.  And therefore let our detractors cease, who are as"|FALSE
626|"blind men judging of colours; let not bats venture to speak of light;"|FALSE
626|"and let not those who carry beams in their own eyes presume to pull the"|FALSE
626|"mote out of their brother's eye. Let them cease to jeer with satirical"|FALSE
626|"taunts at things of which they are ignorant, and to discuss hidden"|FALSE
626|"things that are not revealed to the eyes of men; who perchance would"|FALSE
626|"have praised and commended us, if we had spent our time in hunting,"|FALSE
626|"dice-playing, or courting the smiles of ladies."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XIX"|FALSE
626|"OF THE MANNER OF LENDING ALL OUR BOOKS TO STUDENTS"|FALSE
626|"It has ever been difficult so to restrain men by the laws of rectitude,"|FALSE
626|"that the astuteness of successors might not strive to transgress the"|FALSE
626|"bounds of their predecessors, and to infringe established rules in"|FALSE
626|"insolence of licence.  Accordingly, with the advice of prudent men, we"|FALSE
626|"have prescribed the manner in which we desire that the communication"|FALSE
626|"and use of our books should be permitted for the benefit of students."|FALSE
626|"Imprimis, we give and grant all and singular the books, of which we"|FALSE
626|"have made a special catalogue, in consideration of affection, to the"|FALSE
626|"community of scholars living in ---- Hall at Oxford, as a perpetual"|FALSE
626|"gift, for our soul and the souls of our parents, and also for the soul"|FALSE
626|"of the most illustrious King Edward the Third from the Conquest, and of"|FALSE
626|"the most pious Queen Philippa, his consort: to the intent that the same"|FALSE
626|"books may be lent from time to time to all and singular the scholars"|FALSE
626|"and masters of the said place, as well regular as secular, for the"|FALSE
626|"advancement and use of study, in the manner immediately following, that"|FALSE
626|"is to say:"|FALSE
626|"Five of the scholars sojourning in the Hall aforesaid shall be"|FALSE
626|"appointed by the Master thereof, who shall have the charge of all the"|FALSE
626|"books, of which five persons three and not fewer may lend any book or"|FALSE
626|"books for inspection and study; but for copying or transcribing we"|FALSE
626|"direct that no book shall be allowed outside the walls of the house."|FALSE
626|"Therefore, when any scholar secular or religious, whom for this purpose"|FALSE
626|"we regard with equal favour, shall seek to borrow any book, let the"|FALSE
626|"keepers diligently consider if they have a duplicate of the said book,"|FALSE
626|"and if so, let them lend him the book, taking such pledge as in their"|FALSE
626|"judgment exceeds the value of the book delivered, and let a record be"|FALSE
626|"made forthwith of the pledge and of the book lent, containing the names"|FALSE
626|"of the persons delivering the book and of the person who receives it,"|FALSE
626|"together with the day and year when the loan is made."|FALSE
626|"But if the keepers find that the book asked for is not in duplicate,"|FALSE
626|"they shall not lend such book to any one whomsoever, unless he shall"|FALSE
626|"belong to the community of scholars of the said Hall, unless perhaps"|FALSE
626|"for inspection within the walls of the aforesaid house or Hall, but not"|FALSE
626|"to be carried beyond it."|FALSE
626|"But to any of the scholars of the said Hall, any book may be lent by"|FALSE
626|"three of the aforesaid keepers, after first recording, however, his"|FALSE
626|"name, with the day on which he receives the book.  Nevertheless, the"|FALSE
626|"borrower may not lend the book entrusted to him to another, except with"|FALSE
626|"the permission of three of the aforesaid keepers, and then the name of"|FALSE
626|"the first borrower being erased, the name of the second with the time"|FALSE
626|"of delivery is to be recorded."|FALSE
626|"Each keeper shall take an oath to observe all these regulations when"|FALSE
626|"they enter upon the charge of the books.  And the recipients of any"|FALSE
626|"book or books shall thereupon swear that they will not use the book or"|FALSE
626|"books for any other purpose but that of inspection or study, and that"|FALSE
626|"they will not take or permit to be taken it or them beyond the town and"|FALSE
626|"suburbs of Oxford."|FALSE
626|"Moreover, every year the aforesaid keepers shall render an account to"|FALSE
626|"the Master of the House and two of his scholars whom he shall associate"|FALSE
626|"with himself, or if he shall not be at leisure, he shall appoint three"|FALSE
626|"inspectors, other than the keepers, who shall peruse the catalogue of"|FALSE
626|"books, and see that they have them all, either in the volumes"|FALSE
626|"themselves or at least as represented by deposits.  And the more"|FALSE
626|"fitting season for rendering this account we believe to be from the"|FALSE
626|"First of July until the festival of the Translation of the Glorious"|FALSE
626|"Martyr S.  Thomas next following."|FALSE
626|"We add this further provision, that anyone to whom a book has been"|FALSE
626|"lent, shall once a year exhibit it to the keepers, and shall, if he"|FALSE
626|"wishes it, see his pledge.  Moreover, if it chances that a book is lost"|FALSE
626|"by death, theft, fraud, or carelessness, he who has lost it or his"|FALSE
626|"representative or executor shall pay the value of the book and receive"|FALSE
626|"back his deposit.  But if in any wise any profit shall accrue to the"|FALSE
626|"keepers, it shall not be applied to any purpose but the repair and"|FALSE
626|"maintenance of the books."|FALSE
626|"CHAPTER XX"|FALSE
626|"AN EXHORTATION TO SCHOLARS TO REQUITE US BY PIOUS PRAYERS"|FALSE
626|"Time now clamours for us to terminate this treatise which we have"|FALSE
626|"composed concerning the love of books; in which we have endeavoured to"|FALSE
626|"give the astonishment of our contemporaries the reason why we have"|FALSE
626|"loved books so greatly.  But because it is hardly granted to mortals to"|FALSE
626|"accomplish aught that is not rolled in the dust of vanity, we do not"|FALSE
626|"venture entirely to justify the zealous love which we have so long had"|FALSE
626|"for books, or to deny that it may perchance sometimes have been the"|FALSE
626|"occasion of some venial negligence, albeit the object of our love is"|FALSE
626|"honourable and our intention upright.  For if when we have done"|FALSE
626|"everything, we are bound to call ourselves unprofitable servants; if"|FALSE
626|"the most holy Job was afraid of all his works; if according to Isaiah"|FALSE
626|"all our righteousness is as filthy rags, who shall presume to boast"|FALSE
626|"himself of the perfection of any virtue, or deny that from some"|FALSE
626|"circumstance a thing may deserve to be reprehended, which in itself"|FALSE
626|"perhaps was not reprehensible.  For good springs from one selfsame"|FALSE
626|"source, but evil arises in many ways, as Dionysius informs us."|FALSE
626|"Wherefore to make amends for our iniquities, by which we acknowledge"|FALSE
626|"ourselves to have frequently offended the Creator of all things, in"|FALSE
626|"asking the assistance of their prayers, we have thought fit to exhort"|FALSE
626|"our future students to show their gratitude as well to us as to their"|FALSE
626|"other benefactors in time to come by requiting our forethought for"|FALSE
626|"their benefit by spiritual retribution.  Let us live when dead in their"|FALSE
626|"memories, who have lived in our benevolence before they were born, and"|FALSE
626|"live now sustained by our beneficence.  Let them implore the mercy of"|FALSE
626|"the Redeemer with unwearied prayer, that the pious Judge may excuse our"|FALSE
626|"negligences, may pardon the wickedness of our sins, may cover the"|FALSE
626|"lapses of our feebleness with the cloak of piety, and remit by His"|FALSE
626|"divine goodness the offences of which we are ashamed and penitent."|FALSE
626|"That He may preserve to us for a due season of repentance the gifts of"|FALSE
626|"His good grace, steadfastness of faith, loftiness of hope, and the"|FALSE
626|"widest charity to all men.  That He may turn our haughty will to lament"|FALSE
626|"its faults, that it may deplore its past most vain elations, may"|FALSE
626|"retract its most bitter indignations, and detest its most insane"|FALSE
626|"delectations.  That His virtue may abound in us, when our own is found"|FALSE
626|"wanting, and that He who freely consecrated our beginning by the"|FALSE
626|"sacrament of baptism, and advanced our progress to the seat of the"|FALSE
626|"Apostles without any desert of ours, may deign to fortify our outgoing"|FALSE
626|"by the fitting sacraments.  That we may be delivered from the lust of"|FALSE
626|"the flesh, that the fear of death may utterly vanish and our spirit may"|FALSE
626|"desire to be dissolved and be with Christ, and existing upon earth in"|FALSE
626|"body only, in thought and longing our conversation may be in Heaven."|FALSE
626|"That the Father of mercies and the God of all consolation may"|FALSE
626|"graciously come to meet the prodigal returning from the husks; that He"|FALSE
626|"may receive the piece of silver that has been lately found and transmit"|FALSE
626|"it by His holy angels into His eternal treasury.  That He may rebuke"|FALSE
626|"with His terrible countenance, at the hour of our departure, the"|FALSE
626|"spirits of darkness, lest Leviathan, that old serpent, lying hid at the"|FALSE
626|"gate of death, should spread unforeseen snares for our feet.  But when"|FALSE
626|"we shall be summoned to the awful judgment-seat to give an account on"|FALSE
626|"the testimony of conscience of all things we have done in the body, the"|FALSE
626|"God-Man may consider the price of the holy blood that He has shed, and"|FALSE
626|"that the Incarnate Deity may note the frame of our carnal nature, that"|FALSE
626|"our weakness may pass unpunished where infinite loving-kindness is to"|FALSE
626|"be found, and that the soul of the wretched sinner may breathe again"|FALSE
626|"where the peculiar office of the Judge is to show mercy.  And further,"|FALSE
626|"let our students be always diligent in invoking the refuge of our hope"|FALSE
626|"after God, the Virgin Mother of God and Blessed Queen of Heaven, that"|FALSE
626|"we who for our manifold sins and wickednesses have deserved the anger"|FALSE
626|"of the Judge, by the aid of her ever-acceptable supplications may merit"|FALSE
626|"His forgiveness; that her pious hand may depress the scale of the"|FALSE
626|"balance in which our small and few good deeds shall be weighed, lest"|FALSE
626|"the heaviness of our sins preponderate and cast us down to the"|FALSE
626|"bottomless pit of perdition.  Moreover, let them ever venerate with due"|FALSE
626|"observance the most deserving Confessor Cuthbert, the care of whose"|FALSE
626|"flock we have unworthily undertaken, ever devoutly praying that he may"|FALSE
626|"deign to excuse by his prayers his all-unworthy vicar, and may procure"|FALSE
626|"him whom he hath admitted as his successor upon earth to be made his"|FALSE
626|"assessor in Heaven.  Finally, let them pray God with holy prayers as"|FALSE
626|"well of body as of soul, that He will restore the spirit created in the"|FALSE
626|"image of the Trinity, after its sojourn in this miserable world, to its"|FALSE
626|"primordial prototype, and grant to it for ever to enjoy the sight of"|FALSE
626|"His countenance: through our Lord Jesus Christ.  Amen."|FALSE
